# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antony-preston
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] The ***AA-1* class** was a class of three experimental submarines of the United States Navy, built toward the end of World War I, between 1916 and 1920, intended to produce a high-speed fleet submarine.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] The design was not a success and the submarines saw only limited active service.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] However, the lessons learned were applied to the design of the later V-boats.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] The class was later renamed as the **T-class**.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] These notional "fleet" submarines would necessarily be larger and better armed, but primarily, they would need a surface speed of some 21 knots (39 km/h; 24 mph) to be able to maneuver with the 21-knot battleships the battle fleet was built around.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] This was the designed speed of the *Delaware* class and later battleships, including the Standard-type battleships that were under construction and proposed in 1913.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] In the summer of 1913, Electric Boat's chief naval architect, former naval constructor Lawrence Y.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] Spear, proposed two preliminary fleet-boat designs for consideration in the Navy's 1914 program.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] In the ensuing authorization of eight submarines, Congress specified that one should "be of a seagoing type to have a surface speed of not less than twenty knots." This first fleet boat, laid down in June 1916, was named *Schley* after Spanish–American War hero Winfield Scott Schley.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] With a displacement of 1,106 tons surfaced, 1,486 tons submerged, on a length of 270 feet (82 m), *Schley* (later *AA-1*, and finally *T-1*) was twice as large as any previous U.S. submarine.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] To expedite production Spear simply expanded an existing partial double hull design for a foreign customer without thickening the hull plating or strengthening the framework.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] This resulted in a complicated tank arrangement and a diving depth that was limited to 150 ft (46 m).
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] To achieve the required surface speed, two 1,000 horsepower (750 kW) diesel engines arranged in tandem on each shaft drove twin screws, and a separate diesel generator was provided for charging batteries.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] As the engines were clutched together, it was impossible to perfectly synchronize their operation and that resulted in an unbalanced situation.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] That and other circumstances resulted in poor engine reliability.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] The engineering plant included four New London Ship and Engine Company (NELSECO) 6-EB-19 four-cycle six-cylinder diesels, 1,000 hp (750 kW) each in two tandem pairs, and two Electro Dynamic main electric motors, 675 hp (503 kW) each, directly driven by the engines.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] Two 60-cell Exide batteries provided submerged power.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] One NELSECO four-cycle four-cylinder auxiliary diesel generator was included to charge batteries while the main engines were operating at high speed.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] From 1923 to 1927, *T-3* was re-engined with two German-built Maschinenfabrik Augsburg Nürnberg AG (MAN) four-cycle ten-cylinder diesels, 2,350 hp (1,750 kW) each.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] In addition to the usual four bow 18 inch (450 mm) torpedo tubes, the design incorporated two twin trainable external torpedo tubes in the deck superstructure, immediately forward and aft of the sail.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] These could fire on either broadside, but not dead ahead or dead astern.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] Two 3-inch (76 mm)/23 caliber retractable deck guns were in the original design for the submarines, but they were never installed.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] As with other contemporary U.S. submarine designs, the *AA-1* class was optimized for a high submerged speed, with a small conning tower fairwater and no bridge structure, although "chariot" style bridge structures were later added to all three boats.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] In August 1918 *T-1* was experimentally rearmed with a single 4-inch (102 mm)/50 caliber non-retractable gun at the expense of the forward trainable torpedo tubes, probably to test the effect of a bigger gun on submerged speed as well as provide more anti-ship firepower.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] Larger submarine deck guns were considered because many German U-boats were equipped with guns of up to 105 mm (4.1 in) and some were equipped with 150 mm (5.9 inch) guns.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] The 4 inch gun would later become standard on the S-class submarines.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] The trainable tubes were eliminated from the design by the time AA-2 and AA-3 were commissioned, and only AA-1 was so equipped.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] They were based out of Hampton Roads, Virginia as part of Submarine Division 15 in the Atlantic Fleet and were used for training and maneuvers.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] On August 23, 1917, *Schley* was renamed *AA-1* prior to launching, to free the name for the destroyer *Schley*.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] On July 17, 1920, the three boats were reclassified as Fleet Submarines and given the hull numbers SF-1, SF-2, and SF-3.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] Their names were changed from the AA-series to *T-1*, *T-2*, and *T-3* on September 22, 1920.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] AA-2 and AA-3 never carried those names during their commissioned service, having been renamed into the T-series after launching but before being accepted by the Navy.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] All three boats had been decommissioned by 1923 and placed into storage at Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] Between 1925 and 1927, *T-3* was restored to service in order to test German-built diesels (2,350 hp (1,750 kW) MAN engines), then returned to Philadelphia.
[src:antony-preston/aa-1-class-submarine] All three were struck from the Naval Vessel Register on 19 September 1930 and sold for scrap on 20 November 1930.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] An **aircraft carrier** is a warship designed to carry, launch, recover and support aircraft at sea, equipped with a full-length flight deck and hangar facilities that allow it to serve as a mobile, seagoing airbase.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Typically it is the capital ship of a fleet (known as a carrier battle group), as it allows a naval force to project seaborne air power far from national territory without depending on local airfields for the staging of aircraft operations.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] While heavier fixed-wing aircraft such as airlifters, gunships and bombers have been launched from aircraft carriers, these aircraft do not often land on a carrier due to flight deck limitations.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier, along with its onboard aircraft and defensive ancillary weapons, is the largest weapon system ever created.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] By their tactical prowess, mobility, autonomy and the variety of operational means, aircraft carriers are often the centerpiece of modern naval warfare, and have significant diplomatic influence in deterrence, command of the sea and air supremacy.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the Second World War, the aircraft carrier has replaced the battleship in the role of flagship of a fleet, and largely transformed naval battles from gunfire to beyond-visual-range air strikes.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies use several variants of the aircraft carrier, sometimes categorized as sub-types of aircraft carriers and sometimes as distinct types of aviation-capable ships.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft carriers may be classified according to the type of aircraft they carry and their operational assignments.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Navies have a variety of classification systems for their ships, and a definitive number of current aircraft carriers depends on the specific criteria.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] As of July 2026 there are 9 navies operating 24 active vessels designated by their respective navies as either an "Aircraft Carrier" or "Aircraft Cruiser".
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] These range in tonnage from the United States' 100,000 tonne USS *Gerald R.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford* to Brazil's 21,000 tonne NAM *Atlantico*.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of the types listed here are not strictly defined as aircraft carriers by some sources.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] A fleet carrier is intended to operate with the main fleet and usually provides an offensive capability.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] These are the largest carriers capable of fast speeds.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] By comparison, escort carriers were developed to provide defense for convoys of ships.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] They were smaller and slower with lower numbers of aircraft carried.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Most were built from mercantile hulls or, in the case of merchant aircraft carriers, were bulk cargo ships with a flight deck added on top.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Light aircraft carriers were fast enough to operate with the main fleet but of smaller size with reduced aircraft capacity.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Soviet aircraft carrier *Admiral Kusnetsov* was termed a "heavy aircraft-carrying cruiser".
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was primarily a legal construct to avoid the limitations of the Montreux Convention preventing 'aircraft carriers' transiting the Turkish Straits between the Soviet Black Sea bases and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] These ships, while sized in the range of large fleet carriers, were designed to deploy alone or with escorts.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition to supporting fighter aircraft and helicopters, they provide both strong defensive weaponry and heavy offensive missiles equivalent to a guided-missile cruiser.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The appellation "supercarrier" is not an official designation with any national navy, but a term used predominantly by the media and typically when reporting on larger and more advanced carrier types.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] It is also used when comparing carriers of various sizes and capabilities, both current and past.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] It was first used by *The New York Times* in 1938, in an article about the Royal Navy's HMS *Ark Royal*, that had a length of 800 feet (244 m), a displacement of 22,000 tons and was designed to carry 72 aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since then, aircraft carriers have consistently grown in size, both in length and displacement, as well as improved capabilities; in defense, sensors, electronic warfare, propulsion, range, launch and recovery systems, number and types of aircraft carried and number of sorties flown per day.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first aircraft carrier over 80,000 tonnes full-load displacement was the USS Forrestal launched in 1954.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] In total, the US Navy has had 5 different classes of aircraft carrier of this size definition, the Forrestal class, Kitty Hawk class, the Enterprise class, the Nimitz class and Gerald R Ford Class, two of which were conventional steam-powered and three nuclear-powered.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] USS *Enterprise*, launched in 1960, was the first carrier over 90,000 tonnes full load displacement and *Nimitz*, launched in 1972, was the first over 100,000 tonnes displacement.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] A total of 22 supercarriers have been launched by the US Navy since 1954, with 11 currently in service.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Both China (Type 003) and the United Kingdom (Queen Elizabeth class) have carriers in service with displacements from 80,000 to 85,000 tonnes and lengths from 280 to 320 meters (920 to 1,050 ft) which are described as "supercarriers".
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] France is also developing a new aircraft carrier (PANG) which is to have a full load displacement of 80,000 tonnes and will be considered a supercarrier.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The largest supercarrier in service as of 2024 is the US Navy's USS Gerald R.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford, with full load displacement of around 100,000 tons, length of 337 meters (1,106 ft) and capabilities that exceed those of any other class.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] A US Navy proposal for an aircraft carrier concept with a length of 1,310 feet and a displacement of 500,000 tons full load at a cost of $828 million in 1976 dollars.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Project Habakkuk could be considered an early proposal for an "ultracarrier".
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Several systems of identification symbol for aircraft carriers and related types of ship have been used.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] These include the pennant numbers used by the Royal Navy, Commonwealth countries, and Europe, along with the hull classification symbols used by the US and Canada.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Two months later, on 18 January 1911, Ely landed his Curtiss Pusher airplane on a platform on the armored cruiser USS *Pennsylvania* anchored in San Francisco Bay.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seaplane tender support ships came next, with the French *Foudre* of 1911.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Early in World War I, the Imperial Japanese Navy ship *Wakamiya* conducted the world's first carrier-launched air raid: on 6 September 1914, the *Wakamiya* used its crane to lower Farman seaplanes into the water.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Wakamiya* attacked the Austro-Hungarian cruiser SMS *Kaiserin Elisabeth* and the Imperial German gunboat *Jaguar* in Jiaozhou Bay off Qingdao; neither was hit.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first attack using an air-launched torpedo occurred on 2 August, when a torpedo was fired by Flight Commander Charles Edmonds from a Short Type 184 seaplane, launched from the seaplane carrier HMS *Ben-my-Chree*.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first carrier-launched airstrike was the Tondern raid in July 1918.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seven Sopwith Camels were launched from the battlecruiser HMS *Furious*, which had been completed as a carrier by replacing her planned forward turret with a flight deck and hangar prior to commissioning.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Camels attacked and damaged the German airbase at Tondern, Germany (modern day Tønder, Denmark), and destroyed two zeppelin airships.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first landing of an airplane on a moving ship was by Squadron Commander Edwin Harris Dunning, when he landed his Sopwith Pup on HMS *Furious* in Scapa Flow, Orkney, on 2 August 1917.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Landing on the forward flight deck required the pilot to approach round the ship's superstructure, a difficult and dangerous manoeuver, and Dunning was later killed when his airplane was thrown overboard while attempting another landing on *Furious*.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] HMS *Furious* was modified again when her rear turret was removed and another flight deck added over a second hangar for landing aircraft over the stern.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Her funnel and superstructure remained intact, however, and turbulence from the funnel and superstructure was severe enough that only three landing attempts were successful before further attempts were forbidden.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] This experience prompted the development of vessels with a flush deck and produced the first large fleet ships.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] In 1918, HMS *Argus* became the world's first carrier capable of launching and recovering naval aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] As a result of the Washington Naval Treaty of 1922, which limited the construction of new heavy surface combat ships, most early aircraft carriers were conversions of ships that were laid down (or had served) as different ship types: cargo ships, cruisers, battlecruisers, or battleships.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] These conversions gave rise to the USS *Langley* in 1922, the US *Lexington*-class aircraft carriers (1927), Japanese *Akagi* and *Kaga*, and British *Courageous* class (of which *Furious* was one).
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Specialist carrier evolution was well underway, with several navies ordering and building warships that were purposefully designed to function as aircraft carriers by the mid-1920s.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] This resulted in the commissioning of ships such as the Japanese *Hōshō* (1922), HMS *Hermes* (1924, although laid down in 1918 before *Hōshō*), and *Béarn* (1927).
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] During World War II, these ships would become known as fleet carriers.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier dramatically changed naval warfare in World War II, because air power was becoming a significant factor in warfare.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The advent of aircraft as focal weapons was driven by the superior range, flexibility, and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] They had greater range and precision than naval guns, making them highly effective.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The versatility of the carrier was demonstrated in November 1940, when HMS *Illustrious* launched a long-range strike on the Italian fleet at their base in Taranto, signalling the beginning of the effective and highly mobile aircraft strikes.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] This operation in the shallow water harbor incapacitated three of the six anchored battleships at a cost of two torpedo bombers.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] World War II in the Pacific Ocean involved clashes between aircraft carrier fleets.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Japanese surprise attack on the American Pacific fleet at Pearl Harbor naval and air bases on Sunday, 7 December 1941, was a clear illustration of the power projection capability afforded by a large force of modern carriers.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Concentrating six carriers in a single unit turned naval history about, as no other nation had fielded anything comparable.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] In the "Doolittle Raid", on 18 April 1942, the US Navy carrier USS *Hornet* sailed to within 650 nautical miles (1,200 km) of Japan and launched 16 B-25 Mitchell medium bombers from her deck in a demonstrative retaliatory strike on the mainland, including the capital, Tokyo.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] However, the vulnerability of carriers compared to traditional capital ships was illustrated by the sinking of HMS *Glorious* by German battleships during the Norwegian campaign in 1940.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] This new-found importance of naval aviation forced nations to create a number of carriers, in efforts to provide air superiority cover for every major fleet to ward off enemy aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] This extensive usage led to the development and construction of 'light' carriers.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Escort aircraft carriers, such as USS *Bogue*, were sometimes purpose-built but most were converted from merchant ships as a stop-gap measure to provide anti-submarine air support for convoys and amphibious invasions.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following this concept, light aircraft carriers built by the US, such as USS *Independence* (commissioned in 1943), represented a larger, more "militarized" version of the escort carrier.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although with similar complement to escort carriers, they had the advantage of speed from their converted cruiser hulls.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The UK 1942 Design Light Fleet Carrier was designed for building quickly by civilian shipyards and with an expected service life of about 3 years.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] They served the Royal Navy during the war, and the hull design was chosen for nearly all aircraft carrier equipped navies after the war, until the 1980s.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Emergencies also spurred the creation or conversion of highly unconventional aircraft carriers.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] CAM ships were cargo-carrying merchant ships that could launch (but not retrieve) a single fighter aircraft from a catapult to defend the convoy from long range land-based German aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Noteworthy converted carriers were also USS *Sable* (IX-81) and USS *Wolverine* (IX-64) that both operated on the Great Lakes for training duties and were converted from paddle steamers, making them the only aircraft carriers with this type of propulsion.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before World War II, international naval treaties of 1922, 1930, and 1936 limited the size of capital ships, including carriers.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since World War II, aircraft carrier designs have increased in size to accommodate a steady increase in aircraft size.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The large, modern *Nimitz* class of US Navy carriers has a displacement nearly four times that of the World War II–era USS *Enterprise*, yet its complement of aircraft is roughly the same—a consequence of the steadily increasing size and weight of individual military aircraft over the years.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Today's aircraft carriers are so expensive that some nations which operate them risk significant economic and military impact if a carrier is lost.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies that operate such aircraft carriers treat them as capital ships of fleets, a role previously held by the galleons, ships-of-the-line and battleships.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] This change took place during World War II in response to air power becoming a significant factor in warfare, driven by the superior range, flexibility and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following the war, carrier operations continued to increase in size and importance, and along with, carrier designs also increased in size and ability.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of these larger carriers, dubbed by the media as "supercarriers", displacing 75,000 tons or greater, have become the pinnacle of carrier development.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some are powered by nuclear reactors and form the core of a fleet designed to operate far from home.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Amphibious assault ships, such as the *Wasp* and *Mistral* classes, serve the purpose of carrying and landing Marines, and operate a large contingent of helicopters for that purpose.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Also known as "commando carriers" or "helicopter carriers", many have the capability to operate VSTOL aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The threatening role of aircraft carriers has a place in modern asymmetric warfare, like the gunboat diplomacy of the past.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers also facilitate quick and precise projections of overwhelming military power into such local and regional conflicts.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Lacking the firepower of other warships, carriers by themselves are considered vulnerable to attack by other ships, aircraft, submarines, or missiles.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The resulting group of ships is often termed a carrier strike group, battle group, carrier group, or carrier battle group.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] There is a view among some military pundits that modern anti-ship weapons systems, such as torpedoes and missiles, or even ballistic missiles with nuclear warheads have made aircraft carriers and carrier groups too vulnerable for modern combat.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers are large and long ships, although there is a high degree of variation depending on their intended role and aircraft complement.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The size of the carrier has varied over history and among navies, to cater to the various roles that global climates have demanded from naval aviation.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Regardless of size, the ship itself must house their complement of aircraft, with space for launching, storing, and maintaining them.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Space is also required for the large crew, supplies (food, munitions, fuel, engineering parts), and propulsion.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] US and French aircraft carriers are notable for having nuclear reactors powering their systems and propulsion.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The top of the carrier is the flight deck, where aircraft are launched and recovered.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the starboard side of this is the island, where ship navigation from the bridge and air traffic control from flyco are controlled and (in non-nuclear powered vessels), provides the location of the ship's funnel(s).
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Queen Elizabeth*-class has two island structures; the forward island contains the navigation bridge, while the aft structure houses flyco.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The constraints of constructing a flight deck strongly affect the role of a given carrier, as they influence the weight, type, and configuration of the aircraft that may be launched.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, assisted launch mechanisms are used primarily for heavy aircraft, especially those loaded with air-to-ground weapons.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR is most commonly used on US Navy fleet carriers as it allows the deployment of heavy jets with full load-outs, especially on ground-attack missions.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] STOVL is used by other navies because it is cheaper to operate and still provides good deployment capability for fighter aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Due to the busy nature of the flight deck, only 20 or so aircraft may be on it at any one time.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] A hangar storage several decks below the flight deck is where most aircraft are kept, and aircraft are taken from the lower storage decks to the flight deck through the use of an elevator.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The hangar is usually quite large and can take up several decks of vertical space.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Munitions are commonly stored on the lower decks because they are highly explosive.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Usually this is below the waterline so that the area can be flooded in case of emergency.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] As "runways at sea", aircraft carriers have a flat-top flight deck, which launches and recovers aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft launch forward, into the wind, and are recovered from astern.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Creating such a surface at sea poses constraints on the carrier.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the size of the vessel is a fundamental limitation on runway length.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] This affects take-off procedure, as a shorter runway length of the deck requires that aircraft accelerate more quickly to gain lift.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] This either requires a thrust boost, a vertical component to its velocity, or a reduced take-off load (to lower mass).
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The differing types of deck configuration, as above, influence the structure of the flight deck.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The form of launch assistance a carrier provides is strongly related to the types of aircraft embarked and the design of the carrier itself.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are two main philosophies to keep the deck short: add thrust to the aircraft, such as using a Catapult Assisted Take-Off (CATO-); and changing the direction of the airplanes' thrust, as in Vertical and/or Short Take-Off (V/STO-).
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the recovery side of the flight deck, the adaptation to the aircraft load-out is mirrored.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Non-VTOL or conventional aircraft cannot decelerate on their own, and almost all carriers using them must have arrested-recovery systems (-BAR, e.g.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR or STOBAR) to recover their aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft that are landing extend a tailhook that catches on arrestor wires stretched across the deck to bring themselves to a stop in a short distance.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] If the aircraft are VTOL-capable or helicopters, they do not need to decelerate and hence there is no such need.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The arrested-recovery system has used an angled deck since the 1950s because, in case the aircraft does not catch the arresting wire, the short deck allows easier take off by reducing the number of objects between the aircraft and the end of the runway.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] It also has the advantage of separating the recovery operation area from the launch area.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Helicopters and aircraft capable of vertical or short take-off and landing (V/STOL) usually recover by coming abreast of the carrier on the port side and then using their hover capability to move over the flight deck and land vertically without the need for arresting gear.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers steam at speed, up to 35 knots (65 km/h; 40 mph) into the wind during flight deck operations to increase wind speed over the deck to a safe minimum.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] This increase in effective wind speed provides a higher launch airspeed for aircraft at the end of the catapult stroke or ski-jump, as well as making recovery safer by reducing the difference between the relative speeds of the aircraft and ship.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the early 1950s on conventional carriers it has been the practice to recover aircraft at an angle to port of the axial line of the ship.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The primary function of this angled deck is to allow aircraft that miss the arresting wires, referred to as a bolter, to become airborne again without the risk of hitting aircraft parked forward.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The angled deck allows the installation of one or two "waist" catapults in addition to the two bow cats.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] An angled deck also improves launch and recovery cycle flexibility with the option of simultaneous launching and recovery of aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Conventional ("tailhook") aircraft rely upon a landing signal officer (LSO, radio call sign 'paddles') to monitor the aircraft's approach, visually gauge glideslope, attitude, and airspeed, and transmit that data to the pilot.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before the angled deck emerged in the 1950s, LSOs used colored paddles to signal corrections to the pilot (hence the nickname).
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] From the late 1950s onward, visual landing aids such as the optical landing system have provided information on proper glide slope, but LSOs still transmit voice calls to approaching pilots by radio.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Key personnel involved in the flight deck include the shooters, the handler, and the air boss.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Shooters are naval aviators or naval flight officers and are responsible for launching aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The handler works just inside the island from the flight deck and is responsible for the movement of aircraft before launching and after recovery.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The captain of the ship spends most of his time one level below primary on the Navigation Bridge.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Below this is the Flag Bridge, designated for the embarked admiral and his staff.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] To facilitate working on the flight deck of a US aircraft carrier, the sailors wear colored shirts that designate their responsibilities.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are at least seven different colors worn by flight deck personnel for modern United States Navy carrier air operations.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carrier operations of other nations use similar color schemes.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The superstructure of a carrier (such as the bridge, flight control tower) are concentrated in a relatively small area called an *island*, a feature pioneered on HMS *Hermes* in 1923.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] While the island is usually built on the starboard side of the flight deck, the Japanese aircraft carriers *Akagi* and *Hiryū* had their islands built on the port side.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Very few carriers have been designed or built without an island.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *flush deck* configuration proved to have significant drawbacks, primary of which was management of the exhaust from the power plant.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Fumes coming across the deck were a major issue in USS *Langley*.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition, lack of an island meant difficulties managing the flight deck, performing air traffic control, a lack of radar housing placements and problems with navigating and controlling the ship itself.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another deck structure that can be seen is a ski-jump ramp at the forward end of the flight deck.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was first developed to help launch short take off vertical landing (STOVL) aircraft take off at far higher weights than is possible with a vertical or rolling takeoff on flat decks.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Originally developed by the Royal Navy, it since has been adopted by many navies for smaller carriers.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski-jump ramp works by converting some of the forward rolling movement of the aircraft into vertical velocity and is sometimes combined with the aiming of jet thrust partly downward.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] This allows heavily loaded and fueled aircraft a few more precious seconds to attain sufficient air velocity and lift to sustain normal flight.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Without a ski-jump, launching fully-loaded and fueled aircraft such as the Harrier would not be possible on a smaller flat deck ship before either stalling out or crashing directly into the sea.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although STOVL aircraft are capable of taking off vertically from a spot on the deck, using the ramp and a running start is far more fuel efficient and permits a heavier launch weight.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] As catapults are unnecessary, carriers with this arrangement reduce weight, complexity, and space needed for complex steam or electromagnetic launching equipment.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Vertical landing aircraft also remove the need for arresting cables and related hardware.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Russian, Chinese, and Indian carriers include a ski-jump ramp for launching lightly loaded conventional fighter aircraft but recover using traditional carrier arresting cables and a tailhook on their aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the Russian Sukhoi Su-33 is only able to launch from the carrier *Admiral Kuznetsov* with a minimal armament and fuel load.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another disadvantage is on mixed flight deck operations where helicopters are also present, such as on a US landing helicopter dock or landing helicopter assault amphibious assault ship.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski jump is not included as this would eliminate one or more helicopter landing areas; this flat deck limits the loading of Harriers but is somewhat mitigated by the longer rolling start provided by a long flight deck compared to many STOVL carriers.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United States operates 11 nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carriers, with a total combined deck space over twice that of all other nations combined as of 2016.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] China operates one catapult-assisted aircraft carrier and two ski-jump carriers.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United Kingdom and India each currently operate two ski-jump aircraft carriers, and France operates one nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carrier.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Russia deploys one ski-jump carrier, although it has not been operational since 2017.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the US operates nine large amphibious assault ships with the capability to launch vertical/short takeoff and landing (V/STOL) aircraft, and China operates four amphibious assault ships of a similar size as helicopter carriers.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Italy operates two light V/STOL carriers, and both Spain and Iran operate one V/STOL aircraft-carrying assault ship.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Helicopter carriers are also operated by Japan (4, two converting to operate V/STOL fighters) France (3), Australia (2), Egypt (2), South Korea (2), Thailand (1), Brazil (1) and Iran (1).
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Future aircraft carriers are under construction or planned by China, France, India, Italy, Russia, South Korea, and the US.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Royal Australian Navy operates two *Canberra*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two-ship class, based on the Spanish vessel *Juan Carlos I* and built by Navantia and BAE Systems Australia, represents the largest ships ever built for the Royal Australian Navy.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMAS *Canberra* underwent sea trials in late 2013 and was commissioned in 2014.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Her sister ship, HMAS *Adelaide*, was commissioned in December 2015.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Australian ships retain the ski-ramp from the *Juan Carlos I* design, although the RAN has not acquired carrier-based fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2017, the Brazilian Navy confirmed the purchase of HMS *Ocean* for (GBP) £84.6 million (equivalent to R$359.5M and US$113.2M) and renamed her *Atlântico*.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship was decommissioned from Royal Navy service in March 2018.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Brazilian Navy commissioned the carrier on 29 June 2018 in the United Kingdom.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] After undertaking a period of maintenance in the UK, the ship travelled to its new home port, Rio de Janeiro Navy Arsenal (AMRJ) to be fully operational by 2020.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Before leaving HMNB Devonport for her new homeport in Rio's AMRJ, *Atlântico* underwent operational sea training under the Royal Navy's Flag Officer Sea Training (FOST) program.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] China has had a long-term plan to operate six large aircraft carriers with two carriers per fleet.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is planning a class of eight LHD vessels, the Type 075 (NATO reporting name Yushen-class landing helicopter assault).
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] This is a class of amphibious assault ship under construction by the Hudong–Zhonghua Shipbuilding company.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first ship was commissioned in April 2021.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is also planning a modified class of the same concept, the Type 076 landing helicopter dock, that will be equipped with an electromagnetic catapult system and will likely support launching unmanned combat aerial vehicles.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Egypt signed a contract with French shipbuilder DCNS to buy two *Mistral*-class helicopter carriers for approximately 950 million euros.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two ships were originally to be sold to Russia, but the deal was cancelled by France due to the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2014.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 2 June 2016, Egypt received the first of two helicopter carriers acquired in October 2015, the landing helicopter dock *Gamal Abdel Nasser*.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The flag transfer ceremony took place in the presence of Egyptian and French Navies' chiefs of staff, chairman and chief executive officers of both DCNS and STX France, and senior Egyptian and French officials.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 16 September 2016, DCNS delivered the second of two helicopter carriers, the landing helicopter dock *Anwar El Sadat* which also participated in a joint military exercise with the French Navy before arriving at her home port of Alexandria.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The French Navy operates the 42,000-tonne nuclear-powered aircraft carrier, *Charles de Gaulle*.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Commissioned in 2001, she is the flagship of the French Navy.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship carries a complement of Dassault Rafale M and E-2C Hawkeye aircraft, EC725 Caracal and AS532 Cougar helicopters for combat search and rescue, as well as modern electronics and Aster missiles.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] She is a CATOBAR-type carrier that uses two 75 m C13-3 steam catapults of a shorter version of the catapult system installed on the US *Nimitz*-class carriers, one catapult at the bow and one across the front of the landing area.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the French Navy operates three *Mistral*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] In October 2018, the French Ministry of Defence began an 18-month €40 million study for the replacement of the French aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* sometime after 2030.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, President Macron announced that construction of the next generation carrier would begin in around 2025 with sea trials to start in about 2036.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is planned to have a displacement of around 75,000 tons and to carry about 32 next-generation fighters, two to three E-2D Advanced Hawkeyes and a yet-to-be-determined number of unmanned carrier air vehicles.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has plans for a third carrier, INS *Vishal*, also known as *Indigenous Aircraft Carrier 2 (IAC-2)* with a displacement of over 65,000 tonnes and is planned with a CATOBAR system to launch and recover heavier aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has also issued a request for information (RFI) to procure four Landing helicopter dock displacing 30,000–40,000 tons with a capacity to operate 12 medium lift special ops and two heavy lift helicopters and troops for amphibious operations.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] On February 6, 2025, the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) accepted the IRIS *Shahid Bagheri*, a 41,978-tonne drone UAV carrier converted from a container ship.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] was launched August 2013 and commissioned March 2015.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] the Japanese defense ministry's position is "We are not creating carrier air wings or carrier air squadrons" similar to the US Navy.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] from land bases; according to the 2020 Japanese Defense Ministry white paper the STOVL model was chosen for the JASDF due the lack of appropriately long runways to support air superiority capability across all of Japanese airspace.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] ships "for cooperation and advice on how to operate the fighter on the deck of the modified ships".
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] , marking 75 years since fixed-wing aircraft operated from a Japanese carrier.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Portuguese Navy plans, for the second half of 2026, to receive the NRP *D.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] João II*, a platform ship capable of operating aerial, surface and underwater drones, medium helicopters (Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk) and heavy helicopters (EH101 Merlin) helicopters of the Portuguese Air Force.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] One STOBAR carrier: *Admiral Flota Sovetskogo Soyuza Kuznetsov*: 55,000-tonne *Kuznetsov*-class STOBAR aircraft carrier.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Launched in 1985 as *Tbilisi*, renamed and operational from 1995.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Without catapults she can launch and recover lightly fueled naval fighters for air defense or anti-ship missions but not heavy conventional bombing strikes.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Officially designated an aircraft carrying cruiser, she is unique in carrying a heavy cruiser's complement of defensive weapons and large P-700 Granit offensive missiles.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The P-700 systems will be removed in the coming refit to enlarge her below decks aviation facilities as well as upgrading her defensive systems.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship has been out of service and in repairs since 2018.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The most recent projection stated that repairs would be completed and the ship transferred back to the Russian Navy sometime in 2024, however this projection has not been met as of July 2025, and no updates have been provided.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Russian government has been considering the potential replacement of *Admiral Kuznetsov* for some time and has considered the Shtorm-class aircraft carrier as a possible option.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] This carrier will be a hybrid of CATOBAR and STOBAR, given the fact that she uses both systems of launching aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is expected to cost between $1.8 billion and $5.63 billion.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2020, the project had not yet been approved and, given the financial costs, it was unclear whether it would be made a priority over other elements of Russian naval modernization.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] A class of 2 LHD, Project 23900 is planned and an official keel laying ceremony for the project happened on 20 July 2020.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two *Dokdo*-class 18,860-tonne full deck amphibious assault ships with hospital and well deck and facilities to serve as fleet flagships.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] South Korea had set tentative plans for procuring two light aircraft carriers by 2033, which would help make the ROKN a blue water navy.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, details of South Korea's planned carrier program (CVX) were finalized.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] A vessel of about 40,000 tons is envisaged carrying about 20 F-35B fighters as well as future maritime attack helicopters.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Service entry had been anticipated in the early 2030s.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] In 2025 the program was cancelled and replaced with a drone carrier program.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] One offshore helicopter support ship: HTMS *Chakri Naruebet* helicopter carrier: 11,400-tonne STOVL carrier based on Spanish *Príncipe de Asturias* design.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AV-8S Matador/Harrier STOVL fighter wing, mostly inoperable by 1999, was retired from service without replacement in 2006.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2010, the ship is used for helicopter operations and for disaster relief.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* is a 27,079-tonne amphibious assault ship (LHD) (outfitted as drone carrier) of the Turkish Navy that can be configured as a 24,660-tonne V/STOL aircraft carrier.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Construction began on 30 April 2016 by Sedef Shipbuilding Inc. at their Istanbul shipyard.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* was commissioned with a ceremony on 10 April 2023.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of a sister ship, to be named TCG *Trakya*, is currently being planned by the Turkish Navy.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Sikorsky S-70B Seahawk and the Bell AH-1 SuperCobra are the two main types of helicopters used on TCG *Anadolu*, with the occasional use of CH-47F Chinook helicopters of the Turkish Army during military exercises and operations.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AH-1W Super Cobras will eventually be complemented and replaced by the TAI T929 ATAK 2.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The jet-powered, low-observable drone Bayraktar MIUS Kızılelma and the MALE UAV Bayraktar TB3 are two UCAVs that are specifically designed and manufactured by Baykar Technologies to be used on TCG *Anadolu*.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The maiden flight of TAI Anka-3 (also part of Project MIUS), a jet-powered, flying wing type UCAV with stealth technology, was successfully completed on 28 December 2023.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 19 November 2024, Baykar Bayraktar TB3 UCAV successfully took-off from the flight deck of TCG *Anadolu* and landed on the ship.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] It was the first time a fixed-wing unmanned aircraft of this size and class had successfully landed on a short-runway landing helicopter dock, without the use of an arresting gear.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 3 January 2024, the Turkish government approved the plan for the design and construction of a larger aircraft carrier, named the *MUGEM*-class.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 15 February 2024, the Design and Projects Office of the Turkish Navy announced that it will be a STOBAR aircraft carrier with an overall length of 285 metres (935 ft), beam of 72 metres (236 ft), draught of 10.1 metres (33 ft), and displacement of 60,000 tons.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is to have a combined diesel–electric and gas (CODLAG) propulsion system and a maximum speed of more than 25 knots (29 mph; 46 km/h).
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of the first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier began on 2 January 2025.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier is being built at the Istanbul Naval Shipyard.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two 80,600-tonne (est. full load) *Queen Elizabeth*-class STOVL carriers which operate the F-35 Lightning II.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMS *Queen Elizabeth* was commissioned in December 2017 and HMS *Prince of Wales* in December 2019.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The current US fleet of *Nimitz*-class carriers will be followed into service (and in some cases replaced) by the *Gerald R.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is expected that the ships will be more automated in an effort to reduce the amount of funding required to maintain and operate the vessels.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The main new features are implementation of Electromagnetic Aircraft Launch System (EMALS) (which replaces the old steam catapults) and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] In terms of future carrier developments, Congress has discussed the possibility of accelerating the phasing-out of one or more *Nimitz*-class carriers, postponing or canceling the procurement of CVN-81 and CVN-82, or modifying the purchase contract.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Following the deactivation of USS *Enterprise* in December 2012, the US fleet comprised 10 fleet carriers, but that number increased back to 11 with the commissioning of *Gerald R.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The House Armed Services Seapower subcommittee on 24 July 2007, recommended seven or eight new carriers (one every four years).
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] However, the debate has deepened over budgeting for the $12–14.5 billion (plus $12 billion for development and research) for the 100,000-tonne *Gerald R.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Ford*-class carrier (estimated service 2017) compared to the smaller $2 billion 45,000-tonne *America*-class amphibious assault ships, which are able to deploy squadrons of F-35Bs.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first of this class, USS *America*, is now in active service with another, USS *Tripoli*, and 9 more are planned.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] In a report to Congress in February 2018, the Navy stated it intends to maintain a "12 CVN force" as part of its 30-year acquisition plan.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] A few aircraft carriers have been preserved as museum ships.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently portrayed in a number of Hollywood films including *Midway* (2019) and the carrier USS *Nimitz* is centrally featured in the science fiction film *The Final Countdown* (1980).
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The original film version about the Battle at Midway was made in England and titled *Midway* (1976).
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently featured in both *Top Gun* and *Top Gun: Maverick* as providing the launch sites and mission operations support for the fighter operations seen in both films.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Japanese aircraft carriers involved in the attack on Pearl Harbor are featured in the 1970 film *Tora!
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] Tora!* as well as the more recent film from 2001 *Pearl Harbor*.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier USS *Ronald Reagan* makes a cameo appearance at the end of the 2012 science fiction film *Battleship*.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] In the 2025 film *Mission: Impossible – The Final Reckoning*, the aircraft carrier USS *George Bush* is featured as delivering its special agent to a submarine rendezvous with the nuclear-powered USS *Ohio* in the Bering Straits by Alaska.
[src:antony-preston/aircraft-carrier-p02] The 50-minute documentary titled *City of Steel: Carrier* was released by the Discovery Channel in 2000 covering the final months of building and inspecting the USS *Harry Truman* through its commissioning by President Bill Clinton.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The **Alfa class**, Soviet designation **Project 705 Lira** (Russian: Лира, meaning "Lyre", NATO reporting name **Alfa**), was a class of nuclear-powered attack submarines in service with the Soviet Navy from 1971 into the early 1990s, with one serving in the Russian Navy until 1996.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] They were among the fastest military submarines ever built, with only the prototype submarine *K-222* (NATO reporting name Papa-class) exceeding them in submerged speed.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The Project 705 submarines had a unique design among other submarines.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] However, it also meant that the reactor had a short lifetime and had to be kept warm when it was not being used.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] As a result, the submarines were used as interceptors, mostly kept in port ready for a high-speed dash into the North Atlantic.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Project 705 was first proposed in 1957 by M.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Rusanov and the initial design work led by Rusanov began in May 1960 in Leningrad with design task assigned to SKB-143, one of the two predecessors (the other being TsKB-16) of the Malakhit Design Bureau.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] A special titanium alloy hull would be used to create a small, low drag, 1,500 ton, six compartment vessel capable of very high speeds (in excess of 40 knots (46 mph; 74 km/h)) and deep diving.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The submarine would operate as an interceptor, staying in harbor or on patrol route and then racing out to reach an approaching fleet.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] A high-power liquid metal cooled nuclear reactor was devised, which was kept liquid in port through external heating.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Extensive automation would also greatly reduce the needed crew numbers to just 16 men.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The practical problems with the design quickly became apparent and in 1963 the design team was replaced and a less radical design was proposed, increasing all main dimensions and the vessel weight by 800 tons and almost doubling the crew.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] A prototype of a similar design, the Project 661 or *K-162* (since 1978 *K-222*) cruise missile submarine (referred to by NATO as the Papa class), was built at the SEVMASH shipyard in Severodvinsk and completed in 1972.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The long build time was caused by numerous design flaws and difficulties in manufacture.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Extensively tested, she was taken out of service following a reactor accident in 1980.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] This combined with other reports created some alarm in the U.S.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Navy and prompted the rapid development of the ADCAP torpedo program and the Sea Lance missile programs projects (the latter was cancelled when more definitive information about the Soviet project was known).
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The creation of the high-speed Spearfish torpedo by the Royal Navy was also a response to the threat posed by the reported capabilities of submarines of the Project 705.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Production started in 1964 as Project 705 with construction at both the Admiralty yard, Leningrad and at Sevmashpredpriyatiye (SEVMASH — Northern Machine-building Enterprise), Severodvinsk.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The lead boat – the *K-64* – was built in Leningrad.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Leningrad built three subsequent Project 705 submarines, and Severodvinsk built three Project 705K submarines (only differing in the reactor plant; see below).
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The first vessel was commissioned in 1971.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Project 705 boats were intended to be experimental platforms themselves, to test all innovations and rectify their faults, that would afterwards found a new generation of submarines.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] This highly experimental nature mostly predetermined their future.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] In 1981, with the completion of the seventh vessel, production ended.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] All vessels were assigned to the Northern Fleet.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The power plant for the boat was a lead-bismuth cooled, beryllium-moderated reactor.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Even though 1960s technology was barely sufficient to produce reliable LMRs, which are even today considered challenging, their advantages were considered compelling.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Two power plants were developed independently, BM-40A by OKB Gidropress (Hydropress) in Leningrad and OK-550 by the OKBM design bureau in Nizhniy Novgorod, both using a eutectic lead-bismuth solution for the primary cooling stage, and both producing 155 MW of power.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Designed burst speed in tests was 43–45 kn (49–52 mph; 80–83 km/h) for all vessels, and speeds of 41–42 kn (47–48 mph; 76–78 km/h) could be sustained.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Acceleration to top speed took one minute and reversing 180 degrees at full speed took just 40 seconds.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] This degree of maneuverability exceeds all other submarines and most torpedoes that were in service at the time.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Indeed, during training the boats proved able to successfully evade torpedoes launched by other submarines, which required introduction of faster torpedoes such as the American ADCAP or British *Spearfish*.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] However, the price for this was a very high noise level at burst speed.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Naval Intelligence, the tactical speed was similar to *Sturgeon*-class submarines.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Propulsion was provided to the screw by a 40,000 shp steam turbine, and two 100 kW electric thrusters on the tips of the stern stabilizers were used for quieter "creeping" (low speed tactical maneuvering) and for emergency propulsion in the event of an engineering casualty.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Electrical power was provided by two 1,500 kW turbogenerators, with a backup 500 kW diesel generator and a bank of 112 zinc-silver batteries.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The OK-550 plant was used on Project 705, but later, on 705K, the BM-40A plant was installed due to the low reliability of the OK-550.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] While more reliable, BM-40A still turned out to be much more demanding in maintenance than older pressurized water reactors.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The issue was that the lead/bismuth eutectic solution solidifies at 125 °C (257 °F).
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] If it ever hardened, it would be impossible to restart the reactor, since the fuel assemblies would be frozen in the solidified coolant.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Thus, whenever the reactor is shut down, the liquid coolant must be heated externally with superheated steam.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Near the piers where the submarines were moored, a special facility was constructed to deliver superheated steam to the vessels' reactors when the reactors were shut down.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] A smaller ship was also stationed at the pier to deliver steam from her steam plant to the Alfa submarines.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Coastal facilities were treated with much less attention than the submarines and often turned out unable to heat the submarines' reactors.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Consequently, the plants had to be kept running even while the subs were in harbor.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The facilities completely broke down early in the 1980s and since then the reactors of all operational Alfas were kept constantly running.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] While the BM-40A reactors are able to work for many years without stopping, they were not specifically designed for such treatment and any serious reactor maintenance became impossible.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] This led to a number of failures, including coolant leaks and one reactor broken down and frozen while at sea.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] However, constantly running the reactors proved better than relying on the coastal facilities.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Four vessels were decommissioned due to freezing of the coolant.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Both the OK-550 and the BM-40A designs were single-use reactors and could not be refueled as the coolant would inevitably freeze in the process.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] This was compensated for by a much longer lifetime on their only load (up to 15 years), after which the reactors would be completely replaced.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] While such a solution could potentially decrease service times and increase reliability, it is still more expensive, and the idea of single-use reactors was unpopular in the 1970s.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Furthermore, Project 705 does not have a modular design that would allow quick replacement of reactors, so such maintenance would take at least as long as refueling a normal submarine.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Like most Soviet nuclear submarines, Project 705 used a double hull, where the internal hull withstands the pressure and the outer one protects it and provides an optimal hydrodynamic shape.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The gracefully curved outer hull and sail were highly streamlined for high submerged speed and maneuverability.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Apart from the prototypes, all six Project 705 and 705K submarines were built with titanium alloy hulls, which was revolutionary in submarine design at the time due to the cost of titanium and the technologies and equipment needed to work with it.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The difficulties in the engineering became apparent in the first submarine that was quickly decommissioned after cracks developed in the hull.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Later, metallurgy and welding technology were improved and no hull problems were experienced on subsequent vessels.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] American intelligence services confirmed their suspicions about the use of titanium alloys in the construction by retrieving metal shavings that fell from a truck as it left the St.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The pressure hull was separated into six watertight compartments, of which only the third (center) compartment was manned and others were accessible only for maintenance.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The third compartment had reinforced spherical bulkheads that could withstand the pressure at the test depth and offered additional protection to the crew in case of attack.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] To further enhance survivability, the ship was equipped with an ejectable rescue capsule.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The original test depth requirement specified for Project 705 was 500 metres (1,600 ft), but after the preliminary design was completed, SKB-143 proposed relaxing this requirement to 400 metres (1,300 ft).
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Reducing test depth and thinning the pressure hull would make up for increases in weight of the reactor, sonar system, and transverse bulkheads.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The common myth that the Alfas could dive to 1,000 metres (3,300 ft) or deeper is rooted in Western intelligence estimates made during the Cold War.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] All the systems of the submarine were fully automated and all operations requiring human decision were performed from the control room.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] While such automation is common on aircraft, other military ships and submarines have multiple, separate teams performing these tasks.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Crew intervention was required only for course changes or combat and no maintenance was performed at sea.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Due to these systems, the combat shift of Alfa submarines consisted only of eight officers stationed in the control room.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] While nuclear submarines typically have 120 to 160 crew members, the initially proposed crew number was 14 — all officers, except the cook.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Later it was considered more practical to have additional crew aboard that could be trained to operate the new generation of submarines and the number was increased to 27 officers and four warrant officers.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Also, given that most of the electronics were newly developed and failures were expected, additional crew was stationed to monitor their performance.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Some reliability problems were connected with electronics, and it is possible that some accidents could have been foreseen with more mature and better developed monitoring systems.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Overall performance was considered good for an experimental system.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The main reason behind the small crew complement and high automation was not just to allow a reduction in the size of the submarine, but rather to provide an advantage in reaction speed by replacing long chains of command with instant electronics, speeding up any action.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Two loss-of-coolant accidents occurred in Alfa class submarines.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] In 1971, suboptimal welding on the steam system allowed moisture to leak into an area where it picked up chlorides and then condensed and dripped onto primary coolant pipes containing the liquid metal coolant.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] This caused corrosion and breakage of the primary coolant pipes on Task Order 900.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] A move towards an integral pool-type reactor was considered the appropriate design evolution after this.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The second incident occurred on Project 705K (Task Order 105).
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Steam generator tubes in the evaporator section corroded and leaked steam into the primary system.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Pressure increased in the primary system, which was designed to withstand the full pressure in this incident.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] However, a procedural step mandating that a valve to a sensitive manometer be closed during operation had not been followed.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] As a result, the high pressure could reach the sensitive instrument and broke through it, pouring polonium-contaminated aerosols into the inhabited part of the reactor compartment.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] While the reactor could have been repaired, it was decided to replace it entirely with a new one.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Alfas, as with almost all other nuclear submarines, were never actually used in combat.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] However, the Soviet government still made good use of them, by exaggerating the planned number of vessels, which were assumed to allow naval superiority to be gained by shadowing major ship groups and destroying them in case of war.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The US replied by starting the ADCAP program, and the British Royal Navy the Spearfish torpedo program, to create torpedoes with the range, speed, and intelligence to reliably pursue Alfa-class submarines.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] However, the main thrust of Russian/Soviet SSN development was instead focused toward the larger, quieter boats that eventually became the *Akula*-class submarine.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The technologies and solutions developed, tested, and perfected on Alfas formed the foundation for future designs.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The suite of submarine control systems was later used in the *Akula*-class, or Project 971 attack submarines that have a crew of 50, more than the Alfa but still less than half as many as other attack submarines.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The *Akula*-class submarines represent a hybrid of the Alfa and Victor III classes, combining the stealth and towed sonar array of the Victor III with the automation of the Alfa class.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The material, known as uranium oxide-beryllium, was produced by the Ulba plant in the form of ceramic fuel rods for use by the submarines.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] "The Kazakh government had no idea that this material was there", Kazakh officials later told Harvard's Graham Allison, a national-security analyst.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] In February 1994 it was uncovered by Elwood Gift, an engineer from the Y-12 plant at Oak Ridge, Tennessee, stored in quart sized steel cans in a vault about twenty feet wide and thirty feet long.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Some of it was on wire shelves while others were sitting on the floor.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Word soon came that Iran had officially visited the site looking to purchase reactor fuel.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Washington set up a tiger team, and on 8 October 1994 the Sapphire Team flew out of McGhee Tyson Air National Guard Base in three blacked out C-5 Galaxy cargo planes with 130 tons of equipment.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] It took the team six weeks, working twelve-hour shifts, six days a week, to process and can the 1,050 cans of uranium.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The Sapphire Team finished recanning the uranium on 18 November 1994 at a cost of between ten and thirty million dollars (actual cost classified).
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The cans were loaded into 447 special fifty-five gallon drums for secure transport to the United States.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Five C-5 Galaxys were dispatched from Dover Air Force Base, Delaware, to retrieve the team and the uranium, but four were forced to turn back because of bad weather.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Only a single C-5, carrying 30,000 pounds of supplies Tennesseans had donated for Ust-Kamenogorsk area orphanages, got through.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Eventually a second C-5 arrived, and the two planes carried the uranium to Dover, from where it was transported to Oak Ridge to be blended down for reactor fuel.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] The first vessel was decommissioned in 1974.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Five more in 1990 and the seventh in 1996.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] *K-123* underwent a refit between 1983 and 1992 and had her reactor compartment replaced with a VM-4 pressurized water reactor.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] After being used for training, she was officially decommissioned on July 31, 1996.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] Decommissioning of the ships entailed the singular complication that, the reactor being cooled by liquid metals, the nuclear rods became fused with the coolant when the reactor was stopped and conventional methods for disassembling the reactor were unavailable.
[src:antony-preston/alfa-class-submarine] France's Commissariat à l'énergie atomique et aux énergies alternatives designed and donated special equipment for a dedicated dry-dock (SD-10) in Gremikha, which was used to remove and store the reactors until they could be dismantled.
[src:antony-preston/antony-preston] Antony Preston was born in 1938 in Salford, Lancashire, son of the 16th Viscount Gormanston and Miss Julia O'Mahony.
[src:antony-preston/antony-preston] After becoming a wartime evacuee, he was educated in South Africa at King Edward VII School, Johannesburg, and the University of Witwatersrand.
[src:antony-preston/antony-preston] On his return to England he spent some years at the National Maritime Museum, Greenwich, before becoming Editor of the periodical *Defence*.
[src:antony-preston/antony-preston] During the 1970s he was employed by a specialist publisher, Conway Maritime Press, as editor of their *Warship* annual.
[src:antony-preston/antony-preston] He also produced the specialised newsletter *Navint*.
[src:antony-preston/antony-preston] In the early nineties, he took over as chief editor of the magazine *Naval Forces* at the German editorial group Mönch.
[src:antony-preston/antony-preston] He left to resume as editor of *Warships* in 1996.
[src:antony-preston/antony-preston] Antony Preston lived in London until his death in 2004.
[src:antony-preston/antony-preston] His son Matt Preston (born 1961 and the eldest of Preston's four children) has gained celebrity as a TV judge on *MasterChef Australia* and as a restaurant critic-columnist for the Melbourne Age & Herald-Sun newspapers.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] A **battleship** is a large, heavily armored warship with a main battery consisting of large guns, designed to serve as a capital ship.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] From their advent in the late 1880s, battleships were among the largest and most formidable warship types ever built, until they were surpassed by aircraft carriers beginning in the 1940s.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The modern battleship traces its origin to the sailing ship of the line, which was developed into the steam ship of the line and soon thereafter the ironclad warship.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] After a period of extensive experimentation in the 1870s and 1880s, ironclad design was largely standardized by the British *Royal Sovereign* class, which are usually referred to as the first "pre-dreadnought battleships".
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] These ships carried an armament that usually included four large guns and several medium-caliber guns that were to be used against enemy battleships, and numerous small guns for self-defense.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Naval powers around the world built dozens of pre-dreadnoughts in the 1890s and early 1900s, though they saw relatively little combat; only two major wars were fought during the period that included pre-dreadnought battles: the Spanish–American War in 1898 and the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The following year, the British launched the revolutionary all-big-gun battleship HMS *Dreadnought*.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] This ship discarded the medium-caliber guns in exchange for a uniform armament of ten large guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] All other major navies quickly began (or had already started) "dreadnoughts" of their own, leading to a major naval arms race.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] During World War I, only one major fleet engagement took place: the Battle of Jutland in 1916, but neither side was able to achieve a decisive result.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the Interwar period, the major naval powers concluded a series of agreements beginning with the Washington Naval Treaty that imposed limits on battleship building to stop a renewed arms race.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] During this period, relatively few battleships were built, but advances in technology led to the maturation of the fast battleship concept, and several of these ships were built in the 1930s.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The treaty system eventually broke down after Japan refused to sign the Second London Naval Treaty in 1936.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Although the rise of the aircraft carrier during World War II largely relegated battleships to secondary duties, they still saw significant action during that conflict.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Notable engagements include the battles of Cape Spartivento and Cape Matapan in 1940 and 1941, respectively; the sortie by the German battleship *Bismarck* in 1941; the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in 1942; and the Battle of Leyte Gulf in 1944.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] After World War II, most battleships were placed in reserve, broken up, or used as target ships, and few saw significant active service during the Cold War.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The four American *Iowa*-class battleships were reactivated during the Korean War in the early 1950s and again in the 1980s as part of the 600-ship Navy.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Even at the height of their dominance of naval combat, some strategists questioned the usefulness of battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Beginning in the mid-1880s, the *Jeune École* (Young School) argued that construction of expensive capital ships should stop in favor of cheap cruisers and torpedo boats.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Despite a period of popularity for the *Jeune École*, the idea fell out of favor and the battleship remained the arbiter of naval combat until World War II.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Even afterward, they remained potent symbols of a country's might and they retained significant psychological and diplomatic effects.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] A number of battleships—predominantly American—remain as museum ships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] A ship of the line was a large, unarmored wooden sailing ship which mounted a battery of up to 120 smoothbore guns and carronades, which came to prominence with the adoption of line of battle tactics in the early 17th century.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] From 1794, the alternative term 'line of battle ship' was contracted to 'battle ship' or 'battleship'.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The sheer number of guns fired broadside meant a ship of the line could wreck any wooden enemy, holing her hull, knocking down masts, wrecking her rigging, and killing her crew.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] They also imparted a psychological effect on the crews of smaller vessels.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Ships of the line were also fairly resilient to the guns of the day; for example, the British Royal Navy lost no first-rate (the largest type of ship of the line) to enemy action during the entire 18th century.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Over time, ships of the line gradually became larger and carried more guns, but otherwise remained quite similar.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Development of the first-rates was particularly conservative, as these ships represented a major investment.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] By the early 1800s, the traditional "seventy-four" (so-named because it carried 74 guns) was no longer considered to be a proper ship of the line, having been supplanted by 84- and 120-gun ships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The first major change to the ship of the line concept was the introduction of steam power as an auxiliary propulsion system.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Steam power was gradually introduced to the navy in the first half of the 19th century, initially for small craft and later for frigates.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Early vessels used paddle wheels for propulsion, but by the 1840s, the first screw propeller equipped vessels began to appear.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The value of these smaller steam-powered warships demonstrated their worth, when vessels like the British *Nemesis* proved to be critical to the Anglo-French success in the First Opium War in the 1840s.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The French Navy introduced steam to the line of battle with the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850—the first true steam battleship.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] *Napoléon*, which was designed by Henri Dupuy de Lôme, was armed as a conventional ship-of-the-line, but her steam engines could give her a speed of 12 knots (22 km/h; 14 mph), regardless of the wind.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] This was a potentially decisive advantage in a naval engagement.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The introduction of steam accelerated the growth in size of battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] France and the United Kingdom were the only countries to develop fleets of wooden, steam-screw battleships although several other navies operated small numbers of screw battleships, including Russia (9), the Ottoman Empire (3), Sweden (2), Naples (1), Denmark (1) and Austria (1).
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Concurrent with the development of steam power, another major technological step heralded the end of the traditional ship of the line: guns capable of firing explosive shells.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Pioneering work was done by the French artillery officer Henri-Joseph Paixhans beginning in 1809.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The American artillerist George Bomford followed not far behind, designing the first shell-firing Columbiad in 1812.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The British and Russians began to follow suit in the 1830s, though early smoothbore guns could not fire shells as far as solid shot, which hampered widespread adoption in any fleet.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] By the early 1840s, the French Paixhans gun and American Dahlgren gun had begun to be adopted by their respective navies.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the Crimean War of 1853–1855, six Russian ships of the line and two frigates of the Black Sea Fleet destroyed seven Turkish frigates and three corvettes with explosive shells at the Battle of Sinop in 1853.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The battle was widely seen as vindication of the shell gun.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Despite losing her bowsprit and her foremast, and being set on fire, she was ready for action again the very next day.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] As amply demonstrated at the Battle of Sinop, and again during the Anglo-French blockade of Sevastopol from 1854 to 1855, wooden ships had become vulnerable to shell-firing guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] This prompted the French emperor Napoleon III to order the first ironclad warships: the *Dévastation*-class ironclad floating batterys.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Three of these ships led the Anglo-French attack on the Russian fortress on the Kinburn Peninsula in the Battle of Kinburn in 1855, where they bore the brunt of Russian artillery fire, but were not seriously damaged.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The success of these ships prompted the French and British to order several similar vessels.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In March 1858, the French took development of the ironclad to its next logical step: a proper, ocean-going armored warship.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] This vessel, another design by Dupuy de Lome, was *Gloire*, and after her launching in 1859, Napoleon III ordered another five similar ships, which sparked a naval arms race with Britain.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The first French ironclads had the profile of a ship of the line, cut to one deck due to weight considerations.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Although made of wood and reliant on sail for most journeys, *Gloire* and her contemporaries were fitted with screw propellers, and their wooden hulls were protected by a layer of thick iron armor.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Britain responded promptly with *Warrior*, a similar but much larger ironclad with an iron hull.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] By the time *Warrior* was completed in 1861, another nine ironclads were under construction in British shipyards, some of which were conversions of screw ships of the line that were already being built.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Spain and Russia ordered ironclads in 1861, as did the United States and rebel Confederate States of America after the start of the American Civil War.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Construction of these large and expensive warships remained controversial until March 1862, when news of the Battle of Hampton Roads, fought between the Union USS *Monitor* and the Confederate CSS *Virginia*, firmly settled debate in favor of even larger construction programs.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] From the 1860s to 1880s, navies experimented with the positioning of guns, in turrets, central-batteries, or barbettes; ironclads of the period also prominently used the ram as a principal weapon.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] As steam technology developed, masts were gradually removed from battleship designs.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The British Chief Constructor, Edward Reed, produced the *Devastation*-class ironclads in 1869.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] These were mastless turret ships, which adopted twin-screw propulsion and an arrangement of two pairs of 12-inch (305 mm) guns, one fore and one aft of the superstructure, that prefigured the advent of the pre-dreadnought battleship some two decades later.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] By the mid-1870s steel was used as a construction material alongside iron and wood.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The French Navy's *Redoutable*, laid down in 1873 and launched in 1876, was a combination central battery and barbette ship, which became the first capital ship in the world to use steel as the principal building material.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The rapid pace of technological developments, particularly in terms of gun capabilities and thickness of armor to combat them, quickly rendered ships obsolescent.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the continuous attempt by gun manufacturers to keep ahead of developments in armor plate, larger and larger guns were fitted to many of the later ironclads.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Some of these, such as the British *Victoria* class, carried guns as large as 16.25 inches (413 mm) in diameter, while the Italian *Duilio*-class ironclads were armed with colossal 17.7-inch (450 mm) guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the 1880s, opposition to fleets of large, expensive ironclads arose around the world, but most notably in France, where a group of naval officers led by Admiral Théophile Aube formed the *Jeune École* (Young School).
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The theory, which held as one of its core tenets that small, cheap torpedo boats could easily defeat ironclads, was based on combat experience during the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The doctrine also posited that modern steel-hulled cruisers could defeat a more powerful navy by attacking the country's merchant shipping, rather than engage in a direct battle.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The concept proved to be highly influential for several years, shaping the construction programs of France, Germany, Italy, and Austria-Hungary, among others throughout the world.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In 1889, the British government passed the Naval Defence Act 1889, which embarked on a major naval construction program aimed at establishing the so-called two-power standard, whereby the Royal Navy would be stronger than the next two largest navies combined.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The plan saw the construction of the eight *Royal Sovereign*-class battleships, which have been regarded as the first class of battleship that would retrospectively be referred to as "pre-dreadnought battleships".
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] These large battleships incorporated a number of major improvements over earlier vessels like the *Devastation*s, including a high freeboard for true ocean-going capability, more extensive armor protection, heavier secondary battery guns, and greater speed.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The ships were armed with four 13.5 in (340 mm) guns in two twin mounts, fore and aft, which established the pattern for subsequent battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] After building a trio of smaller second class battleships intended for the colonial empire, Britain followed with the nine-strong *Majestic*-class battleships in 1893–1895, which improved on the basic *Royal Sovereign* design.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] These ships adopted the 12 in (305 mm) gun, which would become the standard for all subsequent British pre-dreadnoughts.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Foreign navies quickly began pre-dreadnoughts of their own; France began *Brennus* in 1889 and Germany laid down four *Brandenburg*-class battleships in 1890.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The United States Navy laid down three *Indiana*-class battleships in 1891, the same year work began on the Russian battleship *Tri Sviatitelia*.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Japan ordered the two *Fuji*-class battleships from British yards, to an improved *Royal Sovereign* design, in 1894.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Navy eventually ordered its own pre-dreadnoughts, beginning with the *Habsburg* class in 1899.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] All of these ships carried guns of between 11 and 13.4 in (280 and 340 mm), save the Austro-Hungarian vessels, which, being significantly smaller than the rest, only carried 9.4 in (240 mm) guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] They also generally carried a light armament for defense against torpedo boats and other light craft.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Some ships varied from this general pattern, such as the American *Indiana*s, which carried a heavier secondary battery of 8-inch (203 mm) guns, and the German *Brandenburg*s, which had six 11-inch guns for instead of the usual four heavy guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Many of the early French pre-dreadnoughts, such as *Charles Martel*, carried a mixed heavy armament of two 12-inch and two 10.8-inch (274 mm) guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Pre-dreadnoughts continued the technical innovations of the ironclad throughout the 1890s and early 1900s.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Compound armor gave way to much stronger Harvey armor developed in the United States in 1890, which was in turn superseded by the German Krupp armor in 1894.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] As armor became stronger, it could be reduced in thickness considerably, which saved weight that could be allocated to other aspects of the ship design, and generally permitted larger and more capable battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] At the same time, the advent of smokeless powder continued the trend begun in the French navy of comparatively smaller guns firing at higher velocities.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Early on in the pre-dreadnought era, most navies standardized on the 12-inch gun; only Germany remained the significant outlier, relying on 11-inch and even 9.4-inch guns for its pre-dreadnoughts.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Similarly, later in the pre-dreadnought era, the secondary batteries grew in caliber, usually to 7 to 8 in (178 to 203 mm) guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the last years of the 19th century and the first years of the 20th, the escalation in the building of battleships became an arms race between Britain and Germany.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The German naval laws of 1890 and 1898 authorized a fleet of 38 battleships, a vital threat to the balance of naval power.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Britain answered with further shipbuilding, but by the end of the pre-dreadnought era, British supremacy at sea had markedly weakened.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In 1883, the United Kingdom had 38 ironclad battleships, twice as many as France and almost as many as the rest of the world put together.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In 1897, Britain's lead was far smaller due to competition from France, Germany, and Russia, as well as the development of pre-dreadnought fleets in Italy, the United States and Japan.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Ottoman Empire, Spain, Sweden, Denmark, Norway, the Netherlands, Chile, and Brazil all had second-rate fleets led by armored cruisers, coastal defence ships or monitors.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Pre-dreadnought battleships received their first test in combat in the Spanish–American War in 1898 at the Battle of Santiago de Cuba.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] An American squadron that included four pre-dreadnoughts had blockaded a Spanish squadron of four armored cruisers in Santiago de Cuba until 3 July, when the Spanish ships attempted to break through and escape.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] All four cruisers were destroyed in the ensuing engagement, as were a pair of Spanish destroyers, and the American ships received little damage in return.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The battle seemed to indicate that the mixed batteries of pre-dreadnought battleships were very effective, as the medium-caliber guns had inflicted most of the damage (which reinforced the observations of the Battle of Manila Bay, where only cruisers armed with medium guns had been present).
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] It also led navies around the world to begin working on better solutions for rangefinding in the hope of improving gunnery at longer ranges.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Conflicting colonial ambitions in Korea and Manchuria led Russia and Japan to the next major use of pre-dreadnoughts in combat.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] During the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905, squadrons of battleships engaged in a number of battles, including the Battle of the Yellow Sea and the Battle of Tsushima.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Naval mines also proved to be a deadly threat to battleships on both sides, sinking the Russian *Petropavlovsk* in March 1904 and the Japanese battleships *Hatsuse* and *Yashima* on the same day in May.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The action in the Yellow Sea began during a Russian attempt to break out of Port Arthur, which the Japanese under Admiral Tōgō Heihachirō had blockaded.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Russians outmaneuvered the Japanese and briefly escaped, but the latter's superior speed allowed them to catch up.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] A 12-inch shell struck the Russian flagship, killing the squadron commander and causing the Russian ships to fall into disarray and retreat back to Port Arthur.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] With night falling, the Japanese broke off and reimposed the blockade.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] At Tsushima, Togo outmaneuvered the Russian Second Pacific Squadron that had been sent to reinforce the Pacific Fleet, and the Japanese battleships quickly inflicted fatal damage with long-range fire from their 12-inch guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In both actions during the Russo-Japanese War, the fleets engaged at longer range (as far as 12,000 yd (11,000 m) at the Yellow Sea), where only their 12-inch guns were effective.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Only in the final stages of the battle at Tsushima, by which time the Russian fleet had been severely damaged and most of its modern battleships sunk or disabled, did the Japanese fleet close to effective range of their secondary guns, fighting as close as 2,700 yd (2,500 m).
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The actions, particularly the decisive engagement at Tsushima, demonstrated that the lessons taken from the Spanish–American War were incorrect, and that the large-caliber gun should be the only offensive weapon carried by battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the early 1900s, some naval theorists had begun to argue for future battleships to discard the heavy secondary batteries and instead carry only big guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The first prominent example was Vittorio Cuniberti, the chief engineer of the Italian *Regia Marina* (Royal Navy); he published an article in 1903 titled "An Ideal Battleship for the British Navy" in *Jane's Fighting Ships*.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Japanese Navy was the first to actually order any of these new ships, beginning with the two *Satsuma*-class battleships in 1904, though due to shortages of 12-inch guns, they were completed with a mix of 12- and 10-inch (254 mm) guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] By early 1905, Fisher had converted to the 12-inch gun for his proposed new capital ships, and in March that year, the German Navy had decided to build an all-big-gun battleship for the planned *Nassau* class.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The American *South Carolina* class was authorized in 1905, but work did not begin until December 1906.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Though several navies had begun design work on all-big-gun battleships, the first to be completed was the British *Dreadnought*, which had been ordered by Fisher.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] He actually preferred a very large armored cruiser equipped with an all-big-gun armament, which would come to be known as the battlecruiser, and he only included *Dreadnought* in his 1905 construction program to appease naval officers who favored continued battleship building.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Fisher believed that Britain's security against the French and Russian threats would be better guaranteed by squadrons of fast battlecruisers, three of which were laid down in 1906.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Regardless of Fisher's intentions, the rapidly changing strategic calculus invalidated his plans and ensured that when the 1906–1907 program was being debated, Germany would be Britain's primary rival, the Royal Navy chose to build three more dreadnoughts instead of further battlecruisers.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Reactions from the other naval powers was immediate; very few pre-dreadnoughts were built afterward, and in the first seven years of the ensuing arms race, all of the major naval powers either had their own dreadnoughts in service or nearing completion.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Of these competitions, the Anglo-German race was the most significant, though others took place, such as the South American contest.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Even naval powers of the second and third rank, such as Spain; Brazil, Chile, and Argentina in South America; and Greece and the Ottoman Empire in the Mediterranean had begun dreadnought programs, either domestically or ordering abroad.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Technological development continued over the decade that followed *Dreadnought*'s launch.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Already by 1910, the British had begun the first of the so-called "super-dreadnoughts" that carried significantly more powerful 13.5-inch (340 mm) guns, all on the centerline.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The United States followed suit in 1911, though increasing the caliber of their guns to 14 inches (356 mm).
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] France adopted a 13.4 in (340 mm) gun for its *Bretagne*-class battleships, laid down in 1912.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] That year, Japan laid down the first of its *Fusō*-class battleships, also armed with a 14-inch main battery.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Germans waited until 1913, but skipped directly to 15-inch (381 mm) guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] By this time, Britain had led the way to the 15-inch gun with the *Queen Elizabeth* class begun in late 1912.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] But more importantly than the increase of caliber, the *Queen Elizabeth*s were the first completely oil-fired battleships and the first fast battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] At around the same time, the United States introduced the next major innovation in battleship design: the all or nothing armor system in the *Nevada* class laid down in 1912.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The heaviest possible armor was used to protect the ship's propulsion machinery and ammunition magazines, but intermediate protection was stripped away from non-essential areas, since this mid-weight armor only served to detonate armor-piercing shells.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] By the start of World War I in July 1914, the Royal Navy's Grand Fleet outnumbered the German High Seas Fleet by 21 to 13 in numbers of dreadnought battleships and 4 to 3 in battlecruisers.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] And over the course of the war, Britain would add another 14 dreadnoughts, while Germany completed another 6.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] German strategy presumed that Britain would launch an immediate offensive into the southern North Sea, but the British preferred to establish a distant blockade, which very quickly stopped German maritime trade.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Both sides were aware that, because of the greater number of British dreadnoughts, a full fleet engagement would be likely to result in a British victory.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The German strategy was therefore to try to provoke an engagement on their terms: either to induce a part of the Grand Fleet to enter battle alone, or to fight a pitched battle near the German coastline, where friendly minefields, torpedo-boats and submarines could be used to even the odds.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The British fleet commander, Admiral John Jellicoe, refused to be drawn into unfavorable conditions and enforced the blockade at the English Channel and between Scotland and Norway.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the Baltic Sea, Germany found itself in the reverse situation, in an even more lopsided fashion versus its Russian opponent.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Russian Baltic Fleet had only four dreadnoughts at the start of the war, so they adopted a purely defensive approach to guard the capital at Petrograd and the northern flank of the Russian army units fighting on the Eastern Front.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the Mediterranean Sea, Italy initially remained neutral, despite being a member of the Triple Alliance with Germany and Austria-Hungary, leaving the latter to face the French Navy and British Mediterranean Fleet alone.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] After ensuring the French army units in French North Africa were safely convoyed to France, the French fleet sailed to the Adriatic Sea to blockade the Austro-Hungarian fleet, which refused to leave their fortified bases.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The French, like the other major European naval commanders, had failed to consider that their opponents would not concede to engaging in battle on terms unfavorable to them.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Adriatic quickly turned into another stalemate as the threat of Austro-Hungarian mines and submarines prevented a more aggressive employment of the French fleet.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Germans embarked on a number of sweeps into the North Sea and raids on British coastal towns to draw out part of the Grand Fleet, which would be isolated and destroyed.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] These included the raid on Scarborough, Hartlepool and Whitby, where the Germans nearly caught an isolated British battle squadron, but turned away, thinking that it was the entire Grand Fleet.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] This strategy ultimately led to the Battle of Jutland on 31 May – 1 June 1916, the largest clash of battleship fleets.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The first stage of the battle was fought largely by the two sides' battlecruiser squadrons, though the British were supported by four of the *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] After both battleship fleets engaged, the British crossed the Germans' "T" twice, but the latter managed to extricate themselves from the action as darkness fell.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Early on 1 June, the High Seas Fleet had reached port.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the course of the fighting, three British battlecruisers were destroyed, as was one German battlecruiser and the old pre-dreadnought *Pommern*.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Numerous cruisers and destroyers were lost on both sides as well.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Germans made two further offensive operations in the months after Jutland.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The first, which led to the inconclusive action of 19 August, saw one German battleship torpedoed by a British submarine and two British cruisers sunk by German U-boats.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] This incident convinced the British that the risks posed by submarines were too great to send the Grand Fleet into the southern North Sea, barring exceptional circumstances like a German invasion of Britain.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the second German operation, which took place on 18–19 October, a German cruiser was damaged by a submarine and the Grand Fleet remained in port.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] By this time, the Germans were similarly convinced of the futility of their attempts to isolate part of the British fleet, and discontinued such raids.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] They instead turned to unrestricted submarine warfare, which resulted in their battleships being reduced to a supporting force that guarded the U-boat bases.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the Baltic, the Germans made two attempts to capture the islands in the Gulf of Riga.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The first came in August 1915, and in the ensuing Battle of the Gulf of Riga, a pair of German dreadnoughts engaged in an artillery duel at long range with the Russian pre-dreadnought *Slava* guarding the minefields that protected the gulf.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Germans drove off the Russian ship, cleared the minefield, but by the time they entered the gulf, submarines had reportedly arrived.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Unwilling to risk the battleships in the shallow, confined waters of the gulf, the Germans retreated.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The second attempt—Operation Albion—took place in October 1917.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] During the Battle of Moon Sound, another pair of German dreadnoughts damaged *Slava* so badly that she had to be scuttled, and the Germans completed their amphibious assault on the islands.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The modern units of the French and British fleets in the Mediterranean spent much of the war guarding the entrance to the Adriatic, first based at Malta and later moving to Corfu.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] They saw very little action through the war.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] For their part, the Italians were content to reinforce the blockading force guarding the Adriatic, as they, too, were unwilling to risk their capital ships in the mine and submarine infested waters of the Austrian Littoral.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Instead, light forces carried out most of the operations.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Meanwhile, several French and British pre-dreadnoughts were sent to attack the Ottoman defenses guarding the Dardanelles.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the ensuing naval operations from February to March 1915, several battleships were sunk or damaged by mines and torpedoes.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] When the fleets failed to break through the defenses, the British and French decided to land at Gallipoli to try to take the fortifications by land; the remaining battleships were thereafter used to provide naval gunfire support.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] This, too, ultimately failed and by January 1916, the British and French withdrew their troops.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Russian battleships saw more action in the Black Sea against their Ottoman opponents.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] By 1916, the Russians had completed a pair of dreadnoughts in the Black Sea, which severely curtailed Ottoman freedom of maneuver.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the course of the war, older pre-dreadnoughts proved to be highly vulnerable to underwater damage, whether by naval mine or ship-launched or submarine-delivered torpedoes.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] HMS *Formidable* was sunk by a German U-boat in the English Channel in 1915.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] At the Dardanelles, HMS *Majestic* was sunk by a German U-boat, HMS *Goliath* was sunk by the Ottoman destroyer *Muavenet-i Milliye*.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The British *Ocean* and *Irresistible* and the French *Bouvet* were all sunk by mines.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] HMS *Russell* and HMS *Cornwallis* were both sunk by mines in the Mediterranean in 1916 and 1917, respectively.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] HMS *King Edward VII* was similarly mined and sunk off the British coast in 1916, and HMS *Britannia* was sunk by a U-boat in the final days of the war.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The French *Gaulois* and *Suffren* were sunk by U-boats in 1916, and *Danton* was torpedoed and sunk by a U-boat in 1917.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] At Jutland, the only battleship lost was the old pre-dreadnought *Pommern*, which was torpedoed by a destroyer.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In contrast, dreadnoughts proved to be much more resilient to underwater attack.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] HMS *Marlborough* was damaged by a torpedo at Jutland, but nevertheless returned to port.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The German SMS *Westfalen* was torpedoed at the action of 19 August 1916, and SMS *Grosser Kurfürst* and *Kronprinz* were torpedoed by the same submarine in November 1917; all three survived.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] SMS *Bayern* was mined during Operation Albion and remained in action against Russian artillery batteries for some time thereafter.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Dreadnoughts lost to underwater attack were rare.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] HMS *Audacious* was sunk by a mine in October 1914, the Austro-Hungarian SMS *Szent Istvan* was sunk by Italian MAS boats in June 1918, and five months later, Italian frogmen sank *Viribus Unitis* using a powerful limpet mine.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the immediate aftermath of the war, the most modern units of the German fleet was interned at Scapa Flow, where in June 1919, their crews scuttled the fleet to avoid it being handed over to the Allies.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The remaining dreadnoughts still in German ports were therefore seized as compensation for the scuttled ships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The postwar *Reichsmarine* of Weimar Germany was limited to a contingent of eight old pre-dreadnoughts (of which two would be kept in reserve) under the terms of the Treaty of Versailles; new battleships were subject to severe restrictions on size and armament.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The surviving battleships of Austria-Hungary, the other defeated Central Power, were soon distributed among the Allies, to be broken up.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] While the other major naval powers remained free to build new battleships, most of them were financially crippled after the war.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The prospect of a renewed naval arms race between the United States, United Kingdom, and Japan, appealed to few politicians in the three countries, and so they concluded the Washington Naval Treaty in 1922, which also included Italy and France.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The treaty limited the number and size of battleships, and imposed a ten-year building holiday, along with other provisions.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The treaty also imposed a ratio of 5:5:3 on total displacement of battleships for the US, UK, and Japan, respectively, and it severed the Anglo-Japanese Alliance.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The only exceptions to the building holiday were for the two British *Nelson*-class battleships, which were permitted to give Britain parity with the latest American and Japanese battleships, which were all armed with 16-inch (406 mm) guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Washington treaty was followed by a series of other naval treaties, including the First London Naval Treaty (1930) and the Second London Naval Treaty (1936), which both set additional limits on major warships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The treaty limitations meant that fewer new battleships were launched in 1919–1939 than in 1905–1914.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The treaties also inhibited development by imposing upper limits on the weights of ships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Designs like the projected British N3-class battleship, the first American *South Dakota* class, and the Japanese *Kii* class—all of which continued the trend to larger ships with bigger guns and thicker armor—never got off the drawing board.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Those designs which were commissioned during this period were referred to as treaty battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The collapse of the treaty system began during the negotiations for the Second London Treaty, where Japan demanded parity with Britain and the US, which the latter two flatly rejected.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Japan withdrew from the treaty system in 1936, though the agreements remained in effect until January 1937.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] As early as 1914, the British Admiral Percy Scott predicted that battleships would soon be made irrelevant by aircraft.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Between 1916 and 1918, US Admiral William Fullam published a series of papers stating that aircraft would become an independent strike arm of the fleet, and argued that the *Lexington*-class battlecruisers then under construction should be converted to aircraft carriers than scrapped.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] By the end of World War I, aircraft had successfully adopted the torpedo as a weapon.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In 1921 the Italian general and air theorist Giulio Douhet completed a hugely influential treatise on strategic bombing titled *The Command of the Air*, which foresaw the dominance of air power over conventional military and naval forces.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In 1921, US General Billy Mitchell used the ex-German dreadnought SMS *Ostfriesland* in a series of bombing tests conducted by the Navy and Army.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The test involved a series of attacks on the stationary, unmanned ships using low-level, land-based bombers dropping bombs that ranged from 550 to 2,000 pounds (250 to 910 kg).
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] *Ostfriesland* was sunk by the heaviest bombs, though Mitchell broke the rules of the tests and the subsequent report concluded that had the ship been crewed, underway, and firing back at the aircraft, damage control teams aboard *Ostfriesland* could have managed any damage inflicted.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Mitchell and his supporters nevertheless embarked on a public campaign that falsely claimed that *Ostfriesland* was a super-battleship, and the quick sinking proved that battleships were obsolete.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Mitchell would eventually be subjected to a court martial, convicted, and discharged from the Army over his insubordinate tactics.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Naval aviation traces its origin back to the first decade of the 20th century, though early efforts were based on using aircraft to scout for the fleet and help direct gunfire at long range.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] A number of experimental aircraft carriers were employed during World War I, primarily by the Royal Navy, all converted from merchant vessels or existing warships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The US Navy completed its first carrier, USS *Langley*, in 1922.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] But aircraft carriers in the 1920s faced a number of challenges to be overcome: aircraft of the day were short-ranged, which meant the carrier had to be very close to the enemy to be able to launch and then recover a strike, which exposed the carriers to attack.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In addition, the available planes had insufficient power to carry meaningful bomb loads.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Early naval aviators nevertheless pioneered effective tactics like dive bombing during this period.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Because the Washington Treaty system precluded the construction of any new battleships until the early 1930s, the major naval powers began a program of modernization for their most effective battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Britain conducted a series of refits to their *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships through the 1920s, adding anti-torpedo bulges, additional anti-aircraft guns, and aircraft catapults; further refits in the 1930s increased armor protection and further strengthened their anti-aircraft batteries.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The *Revenge*-class battleships were less heavily modified during the period.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The US *Florida*, *Wyoming* class, and *New York* classes received similar treatments in the 1920s, while the *Nevada* and *Pennsylvania* classes received new turbines, additional armor, and more anti-aircraft guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Japanese similarly updated their *Fusō*, *Ise*, and *Nagato*-class battleships, and rebuilt three of the four *Kongō*-class battlecruisers into fast battleships, albeit with significantly inferior protection compared to the other ships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] They all also received distinctive pagoda masts.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] *Hiei* was initially disarmed to serve as a training ship under the terms of the Washington Treaty, but was remilitarized in the late 1930s.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In the 1930s, all four classes were lengthened and had their propulsion systems improved to increase their speeds.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The French and Italian navies were exempted from the 10-year building holiday, owing to the comparative obsolescence of their battleships; they were permitted to build 70,000 long tons (71,000 t) worth of battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] But the weak economies of both countries led both to defer new construction until Germany began building the *Deutschland* class of heavily armed cruiser at the end of the 1920s.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] This prompted the French to build the *Dunkerque* class of small, fast battleships armed with 13 in (330 mm) guns, which led to a short arms race in Europe in the mid-1930s.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Italians responded with the significantly larger and more powerful *Littorio* class, armed with 15-inch guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The French, in turn, began the *Richelieu*-class battleships to counter the *Littorio*s.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] By this time, Nazi Germany had signed the Anglo-German Naval Agreement in 1935, which removed the restrictions imposed by Versailles and pegged German naval strength to 35% of British tonnage.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] This permitted the construction of two *Scharnhorst*-class battleships, which were also a response to the *Dunkerque*s.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The advent of the *Richelieu*s prompted the Germans to build the two *Bismarck*-class battleships late in the decade.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The Germans thereafter embarked on the ambitious Plan Z naval construction program, which included a total of eight battleships, of which the *Bismarck*s would be the first two.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] Against the backdrop of European rearmament in the mid-1930s, Britain began planning its first battleship class in a decade: the *King George V* class.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] These were armed with 14-inch guns intended to comply with the terms of the Second London Naval Conference, and they were laid down in 1937.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] The United States began their *North Carolina* class at the same time, and though they were intended to be armed with 14-inch guns, Japan's refusal to agree to the Second London Treaty led the US to invoke a clause of the treaty that allowed an increase to 16-inch guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] In 1939, these were followed by the four *South Dakota*-class battleships, and in 1940 by the first of four *Iowa*-class battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p01] For its part, Japan had decided to embark on a program of four very large *Yamato*-class battleships, armed with 18-inch (457 mm) guns, as early as 1934, though work did not begin on the first ship until late 1937.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The German pre-dreadnought *Schleswig-Holstein* fired the first shots of World War II by initiating the bombardment of the Polish garrison at Westerplatte in the early hours on 1 September 1939.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The German *Scharnhorst*-class battleships caught the British carrier HMS *Glorious* off the coast of Norway and sank her during the Norwegian campaign.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] In the former action, the British sank a pair of older *Bretagne*-class battleships and the fast battleship *Dunkerque*, though the latter was refloated and repaired.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] At Dakar, the French battleship *Richelieu* and other forces fended off the British task force, which resulted in the torpedoing of the battleship HMS *Resolution*, which was severely damaged.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Italy entered the war in June 1940, shortly before the French defeat.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] In November, the British launched a nighttime airstrike on the naval base at Taranto; in the Battle of Taranto, Fairey Swordfish torpedo bombers disabled three Italian battleships, though they were subsequently repaired.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Over the next year, Italian and British battleships engaged in a number of inconclusive actions as they contested the supply lines to North Africa.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] These included the Battle of Cape Spartivento in November 1940 and the Battle of Cape Matapan in March 1941.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] At Matapan, the battleship *Vittorio Veneto* was badly damaged by a Swordfish, though the ship returned to port.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The British battleships *Valiant*, *Warspite*, and *Barham* nevertheless caught a group of three heavy cruisers that evening and destroyed them in a furious, close-range night action.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Convoy battles continued through 1941 and into 1942, with actions such as First and Second Sirte.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] By 1943, Italian operations were sharply reduced due to a shortage of fuel, and after the Allied invasion of Italy, the country surrendered, allowing most of its fleet to be interned at Malta.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] While on the way, the battleship *Roma* was sunk by a German Fritz X guided glide bomb.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] In the meantime, in January 1941, the Germans began to send their few battleships on commerce raiding operations in the Atlantic, starting with the two *Scharnhorst*-class ships in Operation Berlin, which was not particularly successful.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *Bismarck* followed with Operation Rheinübung in May, which resulted in two actions, the Battle of the Denmark Strait and the sinking of *Bismarck*.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] During the operation, *Bismarck* was crippled by Swordfish torpedo bombers, which allowed a pair of British battleships to catch and destroy her.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] By 1942, the last operational German battleships—*Tirpitz* and *Scharnhorst*—were sent to occupied Norway to serve as a fleet in being to tie down British naval resources and to attack supply convoys to the Soviet Union.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The battleship HMS *Duke of York* eventually sank *Scharnhorst* at the Battle of North Cape in December 1943, and *Tirpitz* was destroyed by British heavy bombers in 1944.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] On 7 December 1941, the Japanese launched a surprise attack on the US naval base at Pearl Harbor.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Over the course of two waves of dive-, level- and torpedo bombers, the Japanese sank or destroyed five battleships and inflicted serious damage to the facilities there.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Three days later, land-based Japanese aircraft operating out of French Indochina, then occupied by Japan, caught and sank the British battleship HMS *Prince of Wales* and the battlecruiser HMS *Repulse* off the coast of British Malaya.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Though the Taranto and Pearl Harbor strikes were significant steps toward aircraft replacing the battleship as the primary naval striking arm, the sinking of *Prince of Wales* and *Repulse* marked the first time aircraft had sunk capital ships that were maneuvering and returning fire.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Employment of battleships during the Pacific War was limited by a number of factors.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Japanese strategic doctrine, the *Kantai Kessen*, envisioned a decisive clash of battleships at the end of the war, and so kept most of their battleships in home waters, and only the four *Kongō*s were routinely detached to escort the aircraft carriers of the *Kido Butai*.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] For their part, the US kept its surviving pre-war battleships out of action primarily because they were too slow to keep up with the carriers.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Later in the war, they were employed as coastal bombardment vessels.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Nevertheless, American and Japanese battleships saw significant action during the Guadalcanal campaign in 1942, most notably at the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in November.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] There, an American squadron centered on the battleships *Washington* and *South Dakota* intercepted and sank the battleship *Kirishima*, though *South Dakota* received significant damage in return.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] As more and more of the American fast battleships entered service from 1942, onward, they were frequently used as escorts for the fast carrier task force that was the US Navy's primary striking arm in its campaign across the central Pacific.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] During the Philippines campaign, battleships played a central role during the Battle of Leyte Gulf in October 1944.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The action was one of the largest naval battles in history, which took place over several days and as three Japanese fleets attacked the Allied invasion fleet.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The Japanese battleship *Musashi*, part of Center Force, was sunk by American carrier aircraft during the Battle of Sibuyan Sea on 24 October.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] During the Battle of Surigao Strait the following night, several US battleships that had been repaired from the attack on Pearl Harbor defeated the Japanese Southern Force that included a pair of battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Center Force attacked again on 25 October in the Battle off Samar, but was driven off by destroyers and aircraft from several escort carriers.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] During the Battle of Okinawa in April 1945, Japan sent *Yamato* as a final suicide mission to attack the landing beaches and attempt to stop the invasion of the island.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] American aircraft scored between nine and thirteen torpedo hits and six bomb hits on the ship and sank her.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *Haruna* was sunk by US aircraft off Kure, Japan, in July.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The war ended with the Japanese surrender aboard the battleship USS *Missouri* in September 1945.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] After World War II, several navies retained their existing battleships, but most were either placed in their reserve fleets or scrapped outright.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Of their surviving pre-war battleships, most of the American vessels were either scrapped or sunk as target ships by 1948, though the most modern vessels, those of the *Tennessee* and *Maryland* classes, survived until the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] One of the earlier vessels, USS *Texas*, was preserved as a museum ship.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The four *King George V*-class ships were all broken up by 1957, Only two battleships—the British HMS *Vanguard* and the French *Jean Bart*—were completed after the war.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *Vanguard* did not long outlast the *King George V*s, being scrapped herself in 1960.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *Jean Bart* (and her sister *Richelieu*) remained in the French fleet's inventory until the early 1960s, when they were discarded.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Three of the six American *North Carolina*- and *South Dakota*-class ships were similarly scrapped in the early 1960s, but the other three—*North Carolina*, *Massachusetts*, and *Alabama*—were retained as museum ships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] With the reduced naval budgets of the immediate postwar period, the US Navy chose to concentrate its resources on its carrier force.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Besides the rise of aircraft carriers as the preeminent naval striking force, the advent of nuclear weapons influenced the decision to abandon large battleship fleets.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] In 1946, *Nagato*, which was seized by the US, and four American battleships were used during the Operation Crossroads nuclear weapons tests, though three of the American ships survived the two blasts and were later sunk with conventional weapons.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Of the remaining, smaller battleships fleets, Italy retained its two *Andrea Doria*-class battleships, of 1913 vintage, until the late 1950s and early 1960s, when they were scrapped.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] One other battleship, *Giulio Cesare* was taken by the Soviets as reparations and renamed *Novorossiysk*; she was sunk by a mine in the Black Sea on 29 October 1955.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The two surviving *Littorio*-class ships were taken by the US and UK as war reparations and scrapped in the late 1940s.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The Soviets still had a pair of World War I-era battleships—*Parizhskaya Kommuna* and *Gangut*—but they, too, were scrapped in the late 1950s.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The three large South American navies still had a handful of pre-World War I dreadnoughts in service after the war.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Brazil eventually discarded its two *Minas Gerais*-class battleships in the early 1950s; *Argentina* sold its two *Rivadavia*-class battleships in 1956; the last ship in the region, the Chilean *Almirante Latorre*, followed them to the breakers' yard in 1959.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The four *Iowa*-class battleships were the only vessels of the type to see significant combat after World War II.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] All four ships were reactivated for gunfire support duties during the Korean War in the early 1950s, and *New Jersey* was also deployed during the Vietnam War in 1968–1969 for the same task.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] All four ships were modernized in the early 1980s with Tomahawk cruise missiles, Harpoon anti-ship missiles, and Phalanx CIWS systems, along with the latest radar systems.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] They were recommissioned as part of the 600-ship Navy program under President Ronald Reagan.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *New Jersey* next saw action in 1982, bombarding Syrian artillery during the Lebanese Civil War.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *Missouri* and *Wisconsin* took part in Operation Desert Storm against Iraqi forces in 1991, bombarding enemy positions along the coast.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The ships proved to be expensive to operate, and they required thousands of men to keep in service, so *Iowa* and *New Jersey* were already back in reserve by that time, and *Missouri* and *Wisconsin* were also decommissioned by the end of 1991.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] All four were struck from the Naval Vessel Register in 1995.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] When the last *Iowa*-class ship was finally stricken from the Naval Vessel Registry, no battleships remained in service or in reserve with any navy worldwide.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] A number are preserved as museum ships, either afloat or in drydock.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The U.S. has eight battleships on display: *Massachusetts*, *North Carolina*, *Alabama*, *Iowa*, *New Jersey*, *Missouri*, *Wisconsin*, and *Texas*.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *Missouri* and *New Jersey* are museums at Pearl Harbor and Camden, New Jersey, respectively.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *Iowa* is on display as an educational attraction at the Los Angeles Waterfront in San Pedro, California.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *Wisconsin* now serves as a museum ship in Norfolk, Virginia.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *Massachusetts*, which has the distinction of never having lost a man during service, is on display at the Battleship Cove naval museum in Fall River, Massachusetts.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *Texas*, the first battleship turned into a museum, is normally on display at the San Jacinto Battleground State Historic Site, near Houston, but as of 2021 is closed for repairs.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *North Carolina* is on display in Wilmington, North Carolina.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] *Alabama* is on display in Mobile, Alabama.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The USS Arizona Memorial was erected over the wreck of *Arizona*, which was sunk during the Pearl Harbor attack in 1941, to commemorate those killed in the raid.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Memorials were also placed to mark the wreck of *Utah*, also sunk during the attack.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The only other 20th-century battleship on display is the Japanese pre-dreadnought *Mikasa*, preserved since 1923.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] On 22 December 2025, the United States Navy announced the planned construction of new battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The Trump class will be the first nuclear-powered battleship, and it is planned to carry nuclear-capable cruise missiles, and conventional weapons.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] For much of their existence, battleships were the embodiment of sea power.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The American naval officer Alfred Thayer Mahan argued in his seminal 1890 work, *The Influence of Sea Power upon History*, a strong navy was vital to the success of a nation, and control of the seas was a prerequisite for the projection of force.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Conversely, countries with weak navies would inevitably decline.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Mahan argued that the cruiser warfare advocated by the *Jeune Ecole* could never be decisive, and that only fleets of battleships could control sea lanes and enforce blockades of an enemy's coast.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The book proved to be widely influential across the world's navies; it was translated into German in 1896, where it was used to support the German naval expansion program championed by Alfred von Tirpitz.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] A Japanese-language translation also appeared in 1896, and it soon became required reading at the Japanese naval academy.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] By the end of the decade, Russian, French, Italian, and Spanish versions were produced.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The "fleet in being" in part acts as a deterrent against attack.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The concept underpinned Tirpitz's so-called "risk theory" that was the basis of his program to build a German battle fleet.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Even if the Royal Navy maintained a numerical superiority, the risk that the German fleet would inflict grievous damage even in the case of a British victory would militate against any such battle taking place, and Germany would be free to pursue its global ambitions.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] By the 1890s, naval tacticians had developed a number of formations in which to employ battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The most prominent were referred to as "line ahead" and "line abreast".
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The former, the standard tactic during the age of sail, arrayed ships in a single-file line, which emphasized broadside fire.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The latter placed ships side-by-side, which was suited to close-range melees where ramming and torpedoes could be effectively employed; after Tegetthoff's success at Lissa in 1866 used a modified line abreast formation, the tactic enjoyed a period of popularity for several years.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] By the 1880s, line-ahead tactics had returned to prominence.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Royal Navy officers devised the tactic referred to as "crossing the T" of an enemy fleet, whereby one fleet steaming in line-ahead formation crossed in front of another line of battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] This maneuver would allow one's own battleships to concentrate entire broadsides on the leading enemy ship, while one's opponent could only reply with their forward guns.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Many navies adopted the tactic soon thereafter.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] As the threat of underwater attack, including mines and torpedoes, developed after the 1860s, capital ships could no longer maintain close blockades of enemy ports.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] This required smaller, faster scouts to observe hostile ports so that an enemy fleet could be brought to battle.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Modern cruisers began to be built in the 1880s for this purpose.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Almost immediately after the invention of the airplane, navies recognized its potential as a reconnaissance unit for the fleet's battleships.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The Austro-Hungarian Navy, then following the *Jeune École* doctrine of the 1870s and 1880s, devised the tactic of placing torpedo boats alongside battleships; these would hide behind the larger ships until gun-smoke obscured visibility enough for them to dart out and fire their torpedoes.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] While this tactic was made less effective by the development of smokeless propellant, the threat from more capable torpedo craft (later including submarines) remained.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] By the 1890s, the Royal Navy had developed the first destroyers, which were initially designed to intercept and drive off any attacking torpedo boats.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The other major naval powers quickly followed suit with similar vessels of their own.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The presence of battleships had a great psychological and diplomatic impact.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Similar to possessing nuclear weapons in the second half of the 20th century, the ownership of battleships marked a country as a regional or global power, and the ability to build them domestically signified that a country could claim to be a great power.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Even during the Cold War, the psychological impact of a battleship was significant.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] In September 1983, when Druze militia in Lebanon's Shouf Mountains fired upon U.S.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Marine peacekeepers, the arrival of USS *New Jersey* stopped the firing.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Gunfire from *New Jersey* later killed militia leaders.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] Battleships were the largest and most complex, and hence the most expensive warships of their time; as a result, the value of investment in battleships has always been contested.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] As the French politician Etienne Lamy wrote in 1879, "The construction of battleships is so costly, their effectiveness so uncertain and of such short duration, that the enterprise of creating an armored fleet seems to leave fruitless the perseverance of a people".
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The *Jeune École* school of thought of the 1870s and 1880s sought alternatives to the crippling expense and debatable utility of a conventional battlefleet.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] It proposed what would nowadays be termed a sea denial strategy, based on fast, long-ranged cruisers for commerce raiding and torpedo boat flotillas to attack enemy ships attempting to blockade French ports.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The ideas of the *Jeune École* were ahead of their time; it was not until the 20th century that efficient mines, torpedoes, submarines, and aircraft were available that allowed similar ideas to be effectively implemented.
[src:antony-preston/battleship-p02] The determination of powers such as Germany to build battlefleets with which to confront much stronger rivals has been criticized by historians, who emphasize the futility of investment in a battlefleet that has no chance of matching its opponent in an actual battle.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ***Bismarck* class** was a pair of fast battleships built for Nazi Germany's *Kriegsmarine* shortly before the outbreak of World War II.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships were the largest and most powerful warships built for the *Kriegsmarine*; displacing more than 41,000 metric tons (40,000 long tons) normally, they were armed with a battery of eight 38 cm (15 in) guns and were capable of a top speed of 30 knots (56 km/h; 35 mph).
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Bismarck* was laid down in July 1936 and completed in September 1940, while the keel of her sister ship, *Tirpitz*, was laid in October 1936 and work finished in February 1941.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships were ordered in response to the French *Richelieu*-class battleships, themselves laid down in response to the Italian *Littorio*-class battleships.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The *Bismarck* class was designed with the traditional role of engaging enemy battleships in home waters in mind, though the *Oberkommando der Marine* (High Command of the Navy) envisioned employing the ships as long-range commerce raiders against British shipping in the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] As such, their design represented the strategic confusion that dominated German naval construction in the 1930s.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Bismarck* conducted only one operation, Operation Rheinübung, a sortie into the North Atlantic to raid supply convoys sent from North America to Great Britain.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] During the operation, she destroyed the British battlecruiser HMS *Hood* and damaged the new battleship *Prince of Wales* in the Battle of the Denmark Strait.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Bismarck* was defeated and sunk in a final engagement after a three-day chase by the Royal Navy.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] There is still debate as to the direct cause of *Bismarck*'s sinking, though the majority of experts conclude that scuttling hastened the inevitable foundering of the badly damaged battleship.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] A series of conceptual designs was begun by the *Reichsmarine* (Navy of the Realm) in 1932 to determine the ideal characteristics of a battleship built to the 35,000 long tons (36,000 t) limit of the Washington Naval Treaty.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] These early studies determined that the ship should be armed with eight 33 cm (13 in) guns, have a top speed of 30 knots (56 km/h; 35 mph), and have strong armor protection.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] At the time, the German Navy was constrained by the terms of the Treaty of Versailles that had ended World War I, which restricted battleships to a maximum displacement of 10,000 long tons (10,160 t).
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The sketch design for what became the *Bismarck* class was produced by the Construction Office in 1933 and the final design agreed 1936.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Ministerial advisor Hermann Burckhardt was responsible for the project, and he later supervised the launching of *Tirpitz*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] During this period, the naval leadership grappled with a variety of problems, including the strategic and operational use of such a ship and the preferred propulsion system.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] War games suggested that the new battleships could be used both to attack French shipping at long range and to fight in a traditional battle against the French and Polish navies, then seen as the most likely threats.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Due to the numerical inferiority of the German fleet and the assumption that naval battles would take place at relatively close range in the North Sea, the design staff placed great emphasis on stability and armor protection.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Very thick vertical belt armor was adopted, along with heavy upper-citadel armor plating and extensive splinter protection in the bow and stern of the ships.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The *Reichsmarine* learned in June 1934 that Italy had decided to build a pair of 35,000-ton battleships armed with 35 cm (13.8 in) guns—the *Littorio* class—which would surely provoke the construction of similar ships for the French fleet.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The French response came in the form of two *Richelieu*-class battleships ordered in 1935.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] To keep pace with their French rivals, the next two battleships built by Germany would need to be of a similar size and armament.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] At the same time, Germany was preparing to begin negotiations with Great Britain to secure a bilateral naval agreement that would effectively abrogate the naval restrictions of the Versailles treaty.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] In exchange, Germany would limit its fleet to a third the size of the Royal Navy.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] With the construction of at least two 35,000-ton battleships within reach, the German naval design staff began work in late October to lay out requirements for armament, armor, and speed.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] A preliminary design was completed in November, which resulted in a ship armed with eight 33 cm guns in four twin gun turrets, protected by an armored belt that was 350 mm (13.8 in) thick, and capable of a top speed of 30 knots (56 km/h; 35 mph).
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The staff noted that such a ship would likely exceed the 35,000-ton limit, so triple or quadruple turrets should be considered to reduce the weight.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The design staff had decided that four twin turrets would provide the best solution to distribution of the main battery, as it would provide equal firepower forward and aft, as well as simplify fire control.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] This arrangement was similar to the last German battleships of the Imperial period, the *Bayern* class.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The similarity led to speculation that the *Bismarck*s were essentially copies of the earlier ships, though the arrangement of the main battery along with a three-shaft propulsion system were the only shared traits.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] As design work continued into January 1935, *Generaladmiral* (General Admiral) Erich Raeder, the commander of the *Reichsmarine*, met with the various department and section leaders to refine the design requirements.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The Naval Ordnance Department argued for an increase to 35 cm guns to keep parity with the expected Italian and French ships, which Raeder approved on 19 January.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Another meeting in March saw the Ordnance Department raise the possibility of increasing the projected main battery again to 38 cm (15 in), though Raeder initially rejected the idea owing to the significant increase in displacement.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Nevertheless, though he formally approved the 35 cm version on 1 April, he allowed for the option to increase the main battery depending on foreign developments.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Just a month later, Raeder decided to adopt the larger gun on 9 May, largely the result of Chancellor Adolf Hitler's preference for the 38 cm gun.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] In June 1935, Germany signed the Anglo-German Naval Agreement, which allowed Germany to build battleships at a ratio of 35 percent to the total tonnage of the Royal Navy; this granted Germany effective parity with France, at least in terms of allotted tonnage.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] It also made Germany party to the international treaty system begun at the Washington Conference.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] By this time, the only significant issue to be settled was the propulsion system, which was largely dependent on strategic questions.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Many senior officers in the navy envisioned using the *Bismarck* class in the Atlantic Ocean, which would require a long cruising range.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The naval constructors examined diesel engines, steam turbines, and turbo-electric drive engines; the last system was the preferred choice, as it had been extremely successful in the two American *Lexington*-class aircraft carriers and the French passenger ship *Normandie*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The design staff were also required to provide sufficient range to the new battleships; they would have to make long voyages from German ports to reach the Atlantic, and Germany had no overseas bases where the ships could refuel.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The displacement of *Bismarck* and *Tirpitz* was ultimately limited by the capabilities of existing infrastructure in Kiel and Wilhelmshaven, and the Kaiser Wilhelm Canal, rather than international agreements.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] On 11 February 1937, the Construction Office informed Raeder that the ships could not displace more than 42,000 long tons (43,000 t) due to harbor constraints and canal depths.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The office also expressed a preference for building a third vessel and remaining within the 35,000-ton treaty limit.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Admiral Werner Fuchs, the head of the General Command Office of the Oberkommando der Marine, advised Raeder and Hitler that modifications would be necessary to reduce the displacement to ensure the new ships met the legal requirements of the Second London Naval Treaty.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Japan refused to sign the new treaty, and so on 1 April 1937 an escalator clause permitting treaty signatories to build ships up to a limit of 45,000 long tons (46,000 t) went into effect.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The final design displacement of 41,400 long tons (42,100 t) was well within this limit, so Fuchs's modifications were discarded.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Even though Raeder and other senior naval officers envisioned using *Bismarck* and *Tirpitz* as commerce raiders against first French and later British shipping in the Atlantic, and in fact used them in that role during World War II, the ships were not designed for that mission.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Their steam turbines did not afford the necessary cruising radius for such a role, and many of the decisions made for the ships' armament and armor layout reflect the expectation to fight a traditional naval battle at relatively close range in the North Sea.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The disconnect between how *Bismarck* and *Tirpitz* were designed and how they were ultimately used represents the strategic incoherence that dominated German naval construction in the 1930s.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The *Bismarck*-class battleships were 251 m (823 ft 6 in) long overall and 241.60 m (792 ft 8 in) long at the waterline.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships had a beam of 36 m (118 ft 1 in), and a designed draft of 9.30 m (30 ft 6 in); the draft at standard displacement was 8.63 m (28 ft 4 in), and 9.90 m (32 ft 6 in) at a full load.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships had a designed displacement of 45,950 metric tons (45,220 long tons); *Bismarck*'s standard displacement was 41,700 t (41,000 long tons), and when fully laden, the ship displaced 50,300 t (49,500 long tons).
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships had a double bottom for 83 percent of the length of the hull, and twenty-two watertight compartments.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships were 90 percent welded construction.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The stern was weakly constructed; this had significant consequences on *Bismarck*'s only combat mission.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The building cost of *Bismarck* was 196 million Reichsmarks, while *Tirpitz* was slightly cheaper at 191.6 million *Reichsmarks*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships were very stable, primarily because of their wide beam.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships suffered from only slight pitching and rolling, even in the heavy seas of the North Atlantic.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Bismarck* and *Tirpitz* were responsive to commands from the helm; they were capable of maneuvering with rudder deflections as small as 5°.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] With the rudder completely over, the ships heeled only 3°, but lost up to 65% of their speed.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships handled poorly at low speeds or when traveling astern.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] As a result, tugs were necessary in confined areas to avoid collisions or grounding.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships carried smaller boats, including three picket boats, four barges, one launch, two pinnaces, two cutters, two yawls, and two dinghies.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships had a standard crew of 103 officers and 1,962 enlisted sailors, although the crew of *Tirpitz* expanded to 108 officers and 2,500 men by 1943.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The crew was divided into twelve divisions of between 180 and 220 men.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The first six divisions were assigned to the ship's armament, divisions one to four for the main and secondary batteries, and five and six manning anti-aircraft guns.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The seventh division consisted of specialists, including cooks and carpenters, and the eighth division consisted of ammunition handlers.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The radio operators, signalmen, and quartermasters were assigned to the ninth division.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The last three divisions were the engine room personnel.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] When *Bismarck* left port, fleet staff, prize crews, and war correspondents increased the crew complement to over 2,200 men.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Although both ships were from the same class, there were substantial differences between *Bismarck* and *Tirpitz*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The funnel cap on *Bismarck* was silver-grey, however the cap on *Tirpitz* was always black.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The two cranes on *Bismarck* were sited 3.5 m (11 ft) further outboard and 3 m (9.8 ft) further aft, and *Tirpitz* mounted her two cranes on the superstructure deck.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The 10.5 cm (4.1 in) flak guns (starboard II and port II) were mounted 5 m (16 ft) further inboard on *Bismarck*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] When *Bismarck* was launched she had a straight stem, and *Tirpitz* had the Atlantic bow.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Both ships had a degaussing coil fitted prior to commissioning.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Bismarck* had a single aircraft hangar on each side of the funnel and a double hangar at the base of the mainmast.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Tirpitz* had two double hangars on each side of the mainmast base.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Four minesweeping paravanes were carried, two on either side of the aft superstructure deck.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] These were used in conjunction with the bow protection gear.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The *Bismarck*-class ships both had three sets of geared turbine engines; *Bismarck* was equipped with Blohm & Voss turbines, while *Tirpitz* used Brown, Boveri, and Co. engines.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Each set of turbines drove a 3-bladed screw that was 4.70 m (15 ft 5 in) in diameter.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The three-shaft arrangement was chosen over a four-shaft system, as was typically used on foreign capital ships, since it would save weight.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] At a full load, the high and medium-pressure turbines ran at 2,825 rpm, while the low-pressure turbines ran at 2,390 rpm.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships' turbines were powered by twelve Wagner ultra high-pressure, oil-burning water-tube boilers.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Bismarck* and *Tirpitz* were originally intended to use electric-transmission turbines that would have produced 46,000 shp (34,000 kW) apiece.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] These engines would have provided for a higher top speed, but at the cost of greater weight.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The geared turbines were significantly lighter, and as a result had a slight performance advantage.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The geared turbines also had a significantly more robust construction, and so they were adopted instead.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Both ships were rated for a top speed of 30 knots (56 km/h; 35 mph); *Bismarck* just exceeded this speed on sea trials, reaching 30.01 knots (55.58 km/h; 34.53 mph), while *Tirpitz* made 30.8 knots (57.0 km/h; 35.4 mph) on trials.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] This difference was largely the result of a significant increase in horsepower for *Tirpitz*, which reached 163,023 PS (160,793 shp; 119,903 kW), compared to 148,116 for *Bismarck*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The two ships had different fuel stores; *Bismarck* was designed to carry 3,200 tons of fuel oil, but could store up to 6,400 tons of fuel in a normal configuration; with extra fuel bunkers, the fuel carried could be increased up to 7,400 tons.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Tirpitz* was designed to carry 3,000 tons of fuel, and with additional bunkers, was able to store up to 7,780 tons.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] At 19 knots, *Bismarck* could steam for 8,525 nautical miles (15,788 km), and *Tirpitz* had a maximum range of 8,870 nautical miles (16,430 km) at that speed.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Robert Ballard, the discoverer of the *Bismarck* wreck, noted that the adoption of the three-shaft arrangement caused serious problems for *Bismarck*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The center shaft weakened the keel, especially where it emerged from the hull.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] In addition to retaining greater hull strength, a four-shaft arrangement would have allowed a greater ability to steer the ship using only propeller revolutions than the three-screw system according to Ballard.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] During *Bismarck*'s Atlantic operation in May 1941, the ship's rudder was disabled by a torpedo hit, and her course could not be corrected by altering screw revolutions; this problem had already been revealed during sea trials, but it could not be corrected.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Electric power was provided by a variety of generators, including two electric plants of four 500 kW diesel generators, two electric plants each with five 690 kW turbo-generators, one at 460 kW generator connected to a 400 kVA AC generator and one 550 kVA AC diesel generator.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The generators were manufactured by Garbe, Lahmeyer & Co.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The electrical plant provided a total 7,910 kW at 220 volts.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The *Bismarck*s' use of four twin turrets (the 4 × 2 configuration) was a design practice that hearkened back to the First World War.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Almost all other post-1921 capital ships had triple or even quadruple turrets, which allowed for additional heavy caliber guns, while reducing the number of turrets.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Fewer turrets reduced the length of the battleship's armored citadel (particularly magazine length and the armor needed to protect it) and shortened the vessel itself.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Although triple turrets were considered for the *Bismarck*s, there were concerns that the extra barrel would lower the overall rate of fire in each turret, along with fears that a single well-aimed hit could disable a larger proportion of the ship's firepower.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] It was also felt that four twin turrets allowed for a better field of fire and a more effective sequence of salvos.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships' secondary battery consisted of twelve 15 cm (5.9 in) SK C/28 guns mounted in six twin turrets.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The 15 cm gun turrets were based on the single-gun turrets used aboard the *Scharnhorst* class.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] They could elevate to 40° and depress to −10°; they had a rate of fire of around six shots per minute.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The 15 cm guns fired a 45.3 kg (100 lb) shell at a muzzle velocity of 875 m/s (2,871 ft/s).
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] At maximum elevation, the guns could hit targets out to 23,000 m (25,000 yd).
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] As with the main battery guns, *Tirpitz*'s 15 cm guns were later supplied with time-fused shells.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The decision to mount low-angle 15 cm guns has been criticized by naval historians, including Antony Preston, who stated that they "imposed a severe weight penalty", while American and British battleships were being armed with dual-purpose guns.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Only from the next generation of H-class battleship proposals on, a turret mounted and heavier anti-aircraft defense was designed.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] As built, *Bismarck* and *Tirpitz* were equipped with an anti-aircraft battery of sixteen 10.5 cm (4.1 in) C/33 65-caliber guns in eight twin mounts, sixteen 3.7 cm (1.5 in) C/30 guns in eight dual mounts, and twelve 2 cm (0.79 in) C/30 guns in individual mounts.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The 10.5 cm guns were the same weapons as used aboard the *Scharnhorst* class, and were mounted on the first superstructure deck.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] After *Bismarck* was sunk in 1941, two amidships guns on *Tirpitz* were moved forward so as to provide them with better fields of fire.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships' 3.7 cm 83-caliber guns were twin mounted and placed in the superstructure.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The mounts were hand-operated and automatically stabilized for roll and pitch.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] These guns were supplied with a total of 32,000 rounds of ammunition.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Bismarck* and *Tirpitz* were initially armed with twelve 2 cm guns in single mounts, though these were augmented over time.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Both ships initially carried twenty-four thousand 2 cm rounds.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Bismarck* received a pair of quadruple gun mountings, for a total of twenty 2 cm guns.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Over the course of her career, *Tirpitz*'s 2 cm battery was increased to 78 guns in single and quadruple mountings.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] By 1944 she carried over ninety thousand 2 cm rounds.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The main and secondary battery could be directed from three fire control stations.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] These stations contained either two or three director positions that took bearings of a target through periscopes protruding from the roof.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Above each fire control station an optical rangefinder was mounted in a rotating cupola, and on the front of each cupola the antenna of a FuMO 23 radar was installed.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The main fire control station was mounted on the foretop, the other two stations were mounted fore on the bridge and aft.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] All data from the directors, rangefinders and radar was forwarded to two switch rooms (German: *Schaltstellen*) where it was configured which data was used by the fire control systems (German: *Rechenstellen*) to compute firing solutions for the different guns and targets.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The guns were fired electrically by the fire control system but in case of problems each turret could switch to local control.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] For firing under local control each of the 38 cm turrets and the middle pair of 15 cm turrets were equipped with rangefinders, although the rangefinder on turret "Anton" was removed as it was useless because of seawater spray.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Bearings and distance to targets for the sixteen 10.5 cm anti-aircraft guns were taken from four stabilized anti-aircraft directors.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Two of these directors were mounted on each side of the foretop and the two others were mounted on the centerline, on top of the aircraft hangar and just after turret 'Caesar'.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The four stabilized anti-aircraft directors were of the SL-8 type, which was an improved version of the previous SL-6 type: the gyrostabilization system in the cylindrical base was now motorized which saved a lot of weight.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] By May 1941, only the two forward SL-8 directors on *Bismarck* were equipped with the conical cupola containing the standard rangefinder, the other two still had their temporary equipment in an open position.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] One of the directors on Tirpitz received a Würzburg radar in 1944.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Besides calculating angles and the time of firing of the guns, the anti-aircraft fire control system also calculated the fuze settings which were applied to the shells by a fuze setting apparatus mounted externally to the protective shield of the guns.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The 3.7 cm and 2 cm guns did not have any fire direction control.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The crews of these guns were equipped with portable rangefinders.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The armor plate was mainly Krupp cemented steel.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] This had two classifications, Ww for Wotan (soft) and Wh for Wotan hard.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The *Bismarck*-class ships had an armored belt that ranged in thickness from 220 to 320 mm (8.7 to 12.6 in); the thickest section of armor covered the central portion, where the gun turrets, ammunition magazines, and machinery spaces were located.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] This portion of the belt was capped on either end by 220 mm thick transverse bulkheads.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ships had an upper deck that was 50 mm (2 in) thick, and an armored deck that was between 100 and 120 mm (3.9 and 4.7 in) thick amidships, and tapered down to 60 mm (2.4 in) at the bow and 80 mm (3.1 in) at the stern.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The deck was mounted low in the hull, however, which reduced the volume of internal space protected by the armored citadel.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] This contrasted with contemporary British and American designs that featured a single thick armored deck mounted high in the ship.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The forward conning tower had a 200 mm (7.9 in) thick roof and 350 mm (13.8 in) thick sides, while the range finder had an armored roof 100 mm (4 in) thick and 200 mm (8 in) thick sides.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The aft conning tower had much lighter armor: the roof was 50 mm thick and the sides were 150 mm (5.9 in), while the aft range finder had a 50 mm thick roof and 100 mm sides.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The main battery turrets were reasonably well-protected: the turret forward roofs were 180 mm (7.1 in) and roof rears were 130 mm (5.1 in) thick, the sides were 220 mm thick, and the faces were 360 mm (14 in) thick with 220 mm (8.7 in) thick shields.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] These armor thicknesses were less than those of contemporary British (*King George V*) and French (*Richelieu*) designs.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Conversely, the secondary battery was better-protected than most rivals.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The 15 cm gun turrets had 35 mm (1.4 in) thick roofs, 40 mm (1.6 in) sides, and 100 mm fronts.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Regarding underwater protection, the armor was resistant to a 250 kg TNT explosive charge.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Armor depth was 5.5 meters (216.5 in), with the longitudinal bulkhead thickness being 53 mm (2.1 in).
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Overall bottom protection had a depth of 1.7 meters (66.9 in).
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The citadel could resist a hit from a 38 cm shell of a weight of 1,016 kg fired from ranges between 10,793 meters and 21,031 meters for the machinery, and from 23,319 meters for the magazine.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] After *Bismarck* joined the fleet, plans were drawn up for a sortie into the North Atlantic, which was codenamed Operation Rheinübung (Rhine Exercise).
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The operation initially called for a force composed of *Bismarck*, *Tirpitz*, and the two *Scharnhorst*-class battleships.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Tirpitz* was not yet ready for service by May 1941, and *Scharnhorst* was being overhauled.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The force was reduced to *Bismarck*, *Gneisenau*, and the heavy cruiser *Prinz Eugen*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Gneisenau* was damaged by a British bombing raid on Brest, so it was decided that only *Bismarck* and *Prinz Eugen* would conduct the operation.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Admiral Günther Lütjens was placed in command of the pair of ships.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Early on the morning of 19 May, *Bismarck* left Gotenhafen, bound for the North Atlantic.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] While on the trip through the Danish Belt, *Bismarck* and *Prinz Eugen* encountered the Swedish cruiser HSwMS *Gotland* in Kattegat; the sighting was passed through the Swedish Navy to the British naval attaché in Stockholm.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The British Royal Air Force conducted aerial reconnaissance of the Norwegian fjord in which *Bismarck* and *Prinz Eugen* had stopped, to confirm the sighting.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] While in Norway, Lütjens failed to replenish the approximately 1,000 long tons (1,016 t) of fuel *Bismarck* had spent on the first leg of the voyage.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] By 23 May, *Bismarck* and *Prinz Eugen* had reached the Denmark Strait.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] That evening, the British cruisers *Suffolk* and *Norfolk* briefly engaged *Bismarck* before dropping back to shadow the German ships.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] At 06:00 the following morning, observers aboard *Bismarck* spotted the masts of the battlecruiser *Hood* and the new battleship *Prince of Wales*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The British ships steamed directly towards *Bismarck* and *Prinz Eugen*, before attempting a turn to bring the two forces on a roughly parallel course.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] During the turn, at least one of *Bismarck*'s 38 cm shells penetrated one of the aft ammunition magazines aboard *Hood*, which caused a catastrophic explosion and destroyed the ship.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] There were only three survivors from *Hood*'s crew of 1,421.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The German ships then concentrated their fire on *Prince of Wales*, which was forced to withdraw.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Bismarck* did not emerge unscathed; a direct hit on her bow from *Prince of Wales* caused *Bismarck* to take in some 2,000 long tons (2,032 t) of water.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The ship was also leaking oil, which made it easier for the British to track her.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] After retreating, *Prince of Wales* joined *Norfolk* and *Suffolk*; the ships briefly engaged *Bismarck* at around 18:00.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] By this time, 19 warships were involved in the chase.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] This included six battleships and battlecruisers and two aircraft carriers, along with a number of cruisers and destroyers.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] After the second engagement with *Prince of Wales*, Lütjens detached *Prinz Eugen* to continue the operation while *Bismarck* sailed for port.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Shortly before midnight on 24 May, a group of Fairey Swordfish torpedo bombers from 825 Naval Air Squadron on *Victorious* attacked *Bismarck*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] One torpedo struck the ship amidships, though without doing any serious damage.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The shock from the explosion, coupled with *Bismarck*'s maneuvering at high speed, damaged the temporary repairs that had stopped the flooding from the earlier battle damage.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Her speed was reduced to 16 knots (30 km/h; 18 mph) to slow the flooding while repair teams fixed the reopened wounds.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Early on 25 May, *Bismarck* doubled back past her pursuers in a wide circle.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The maneuver successfully shook off the British ships, which turned west in an attempt to find the ship.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Despite the maneuver, Lütjens was unaware that he had evaded the British, and so sent a series of radio transmissions, which were intercepted by the British and used to gain a rough fix on his position.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Due to the damage his ship had sustained, Lütjens decided to head for occupied France rather than continue his mission.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] On the morning of 26 May, a Coastal Command PBY Catalina flying boat spotted *Bismarck* 690 nmi (1,280 km; 790 mi) to the north-west of Brest; she was steaming at a speed that would put her under the protective umbrella of German aircraft and U-boats within 24 hours.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The only British forces close enough to slow her down were the aircraft carrier *Ark Royal* and her escort, the battlecruiser *Renown*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] At approximately 20:30, a flight of fifteen *Ark Royal*'s 820 Naval Air Squadrons Swordfish torpedo bombers launched an attack on *Bismarck*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Three torpedoes were believed to have struck the ship; the first two torpedoes failed to do serious damage to the ship, but the third hit jammed *Bismarck*'s rudders hard to starboard.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The damage could not be repaired, and the battleship began turning in a large circle, back towards her pursuers.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] An hour after the Swordfish attack, Lütjens transmitted the following signal to Naval Group Command West: "Ship unable to maneuver.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Long live the Führer." At 08:47 the following morning, the battleship *Rodney* opened fire, followed directly by *King George V*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Bismarck* replied three minutes later, though at 09:02 a 16-inch shell from *Rodney* destroyed the forward turrets.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Half an hour later, *Bismarck*'s rear turrets were silenced as well.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] At around 10:15, both British battleships had ceased fire, their target a burning wreck.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The British were running dangerously low on fuel, but *Bismarck*, although aflame and foundering, had not yet sunk.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The cruiser *Dorsetshire* fired several torpedoes into the crippled ship, which then took on a severe list to port.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] At approximately the same time as *Dorsetshire*'s attack, engine room crew detonated scuttling charges in the engine rooms.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Only 110 men were rescued by the British before reports of U-boats forced them from the scene.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] A further five men were rescued by German vessels.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] On 6 March, *Tirpitz*, escorted by the destroyers *Z25*, *Z14 Friedrich Ihn*, *Z5 Paul Jacobi* and *Z7 Hermann Schoemann*, launched a raid on the British convoys to the Soviet Union.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The Germans attempted to intercept convoys PQ-12 and QP-8, but the inclement weather prevented them from finding the convoys.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] A Soviet freighter that was sailing independently of the convoys was sunk by the destroyers.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The British submarines *Trident* and *Seawolf* reported *Tirpitz*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] A Home Fleet squadron consisting of the battleships *King George V* and *Duke of York*, the aircraft carrier *Victorious*, the heavy cruiser *Berwick* and destroyers failed to find the Germans.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Victorious* launched a strike of twelve Fairey Albacore torpedo bombers, however the aircraft were repulsed without having scored any hits on the German ships.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Tirpitz* and the destroyers were back in port by 12 March.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The close call prompted Hitler to mandate that *Tirpitz* was not to attack another convoy unless its escorting aircraft carrier had been sunk or disabled.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The RAF launched a series of unsuccessful bombing raids against *Tirpitz* while she was moored in the Faettenfjord.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The first on 30/31 January by seven Short Stirling of No 15 Squadron and nine Handley Page Halifax bombers of No 76 Squadron.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Next came a raid by 36 Halifax bombers, took place on 30/31 March.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] On 27/28 April, *Tirpitz* was attacked by 26 Halifax bombers of No 4 Group and 10 Avro Lancasters of No 5 Group.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] This was followed on 28/29 April by 23 Halifaxes of No 76 Squadron and 11 Lancasters.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] A combination of heavy German anti-aircraft fire and poor weather caused all three missions to fail.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Over the rest of the year and into late 1942, *Tirpitz* underwent a refit in the Faettenfjord, which lacked dockyard facilities of any type.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] As a result, the work was done incrementally; a large caisson was built to allow the rudders to be replaced.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] In January 1943, *Tirpitz* emerged from the lengthy overhaul, after which she was transferred to Altafjord.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Here, she participated in extensive training operations with *Scharnhorst* and the heavy cruiser *Lützow*, which lasted until the middle of the year.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] On 6 September, *Tirpitz*, *Scharnhorst*, and the destroyers *Z27*, *Z29*, *Z30*, *Z31*, *Z33*, *Z15 Erich Steinbrinck*, *Z20 Karl Galster*, *Z10 Hans Lody* and *Z6 Theodor Riedel* bombarded the island of Spitzbergen, which served as a British refueling station.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The two battleships destroyed their targets and returned safely to Altenfjord; this was the first time *Tirpitz* fired her main guns in anger.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] On 22/23 September 1943, six British midget submarines attacked *Tirpitz* while at anchor.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Only two of the submarines, X6 and X7 successfully planted explosive charges against the battleship's hull.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The first charge exploded at 0812, the second shortly afterwards.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Very extensive damage was sustained; nearly all electric lighting failed, partial flooding of electric switchboard room 2, flooding of the double bottom and fuel bunkers on the port side.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Structural damage in the engine plant of the housing and components of the port turbine and condenser; the tail shafts were out of alignment, the thrust bearing was damaged, the propellers were immobilized, and the port rudder assembly was flooded.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The main gun turrets had been jolted off their roller tracks, only one rangefinder was still active, one 15 cm turret was jammed, three of four fire control centers were damaged, the aircraft catapult was inoperable and two Arado 196 floatplanes were seriously damaged.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Casualties were light however, one dead and 40 wounded.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] *Tirpitz* had been successfully neutralized.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Over the next six months, a workforce of some 1,000 men effected the needed repairs, which were finished by March 1944.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The British resumed the series of air attacks almost immediately after repairs were completed.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] On 3 April, the Royal Navy launched Operation Tungsten, during which 40 fighters and 40 Barracuda bombers from six carriers attacked the ship.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] They scored 15 direct hits and two near misses, which caused heavy damage, killed 122 men, and wounded 316 more.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The Royal Navy attempted to repeat the attack three weeks later on the 24th, but had to call the operation off due to inclement weather.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Operation Brawn, another carrier-launched attack, followed on 15 May, but again weather interfered.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Another carrier strike was attempted on 28 May, but it too was cancelled due to poor weather conditions.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Operation Mascot, which was to be conducted by the carriers *Victorious*, *Furious*, and *Indefatigable* on 17 July, was frustrated by the heavy smokescreen over the battleship.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The Royal Navy launched the Operation Goodwood series in late August.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Goodwood I took place on 22 August, with 38 bombers and 43 fighters from five carriers.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Goodwood III followed two days later, with 48 bombers and 29 fighters from *Formidable*, *Furious*, and *Indefatigable*.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The bombers made two hits on the ship, which did only minor damage.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The last Royal Navy operation, Goodwood IV, followed on 29 August.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Thirty-four bombers and 25 fighters, launched from *Formidable* and *Indefatigable*, attacked the ship, though fog prevented them from scoring any hits.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The task of sinking *Tirpitz* now fell to the RAF, which performed three airstrikes armed with new 5,400 kg (11,900 lb) Tallboy bombs.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The first attack, Operation Paravane, came on 15 September, when a force of 27 Lancasters dropped a single Tallboy each; the bombers succeeded in hitting *Tirpitz* directly in the bow with one of the bombs.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The bomb completely penetrated the ship and exploded directly under her keel.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] This caused 1,500 long tons (1,524 t) of water to flood the ship; *Tirpitz* had again been disabled.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] A month later, on 15 October, *Tirpitz* was moved to Håkøya Island off Tromsø to be used as a floating artillery battery.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Two weeks later, on 29 October, the British launched Operation Obviate, which consisted of 32 Lancaster bombers.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Only a near miss was achieved, though it caused *Tirpitz* to take in more water.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The last attack, Operation Catechism, took place on 12 November.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Thirty-two Lancasters attacked the ship and scored a pair of direct hits and a near miss.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The bombs detonated one of *Tirpitz*'s ammunition magazines and caused the ship to capsize.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Casualties were high: 1,204 men were killed in the attack.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] Another 806 men managed to escape the sinking ship, and a further 82 were rescued from the capsized hulk.
[src:antony-preston/bismarck-class-battleship] The wreck was gradually broken up for scrap between 1948 and 1957.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The ***Borodino*-class battleship**s were a group of five pre-dreadnought battleships built for the Imperial Russian Navy around the end of the 19th century.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Their design was based on that of the French-built *Tsesarevich* modified to use Russian equipment.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The first four ships were finished after the start of the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905 and were among the ships ordered to sail from the Baltic Sea to the Far East to relieve the Pacific Squadron besieged by the Japanese in Port Arthur.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Three of these ships were sunk and one was captured by the Imperial Japanese Navy at the Battle of Tsushima in 1905.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The fifth and final ship, *Slava*, was not completed in time to participate in the war and served with the Baltic Fleet through World War I.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Tsar Nicholas II had desired a warm-water port on the Pacific since his accession to the throne in 1894.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] He achieved this ambition in March 1898 when Russia signed a 25-year lease for Port Arthur and the Liaotung Peninsula with China.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Japan invested much of the indemnity money in expanding its fleet, while Russia began a major building programme ("For the Needs of the Far East") to defend its newly acquired port that included the *Borodino*-class battleships.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The *Borodino*s were the most numerous class of battleships ever built by Russia.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Although they were intended to be near duplicates of *Tsesarevich*, as soon as the contracts were signed, it became clear that they would be quite different from the French-built ship.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The basic problem facing the navy was that the *Borodinos* would have heavier engines and larger turrets which would require a designer to build a ship which had the same speed, draft, guns and armor as *Tsesarevich*, but a greater displacement.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Skvortsov of the Naval Technical Committee (NTC).
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] He completed his new design in July/August 1898, one month after the original contract had been signed.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] As might be expected, the *Borodino*s greatly resembled *Tsesarevich*, although Skvortsov added two more casemates, each containing four 75-millimeter (3.0 in) guns, one at the bow and the other aft.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] These guns were added to the already existing dozen 75 mm guns emplaced along the sides above the armor belt.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] This caused the tumblehome used on the rest of the hull to be deleted over the twelve guns and flat-sided armor was used in its place.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Thus the five *Borodino*-class battleships had tumblehome hulls only fore and aft of their 75 mm guns emplaced along their sides.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The centreline bulkhead between the engine and boiler rooms caused a danger of capsizing if one side flooded and the narrow belt armor became submerged when overloaded.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] As such, naval historian Antony Preston regarded these as some of the worst battleships ever built.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The ships were 389 feet 5 inches (118.7 m) long at the waterline and 397 feet 3 inches (121.1 m) long overall, with a beam of 76 feet 1 inch (23.2 m) and a draft of 29 feet 2 inches (8.9 m), 38 inches (965 mm) more than designed.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] They were designed for a crew of 28 officers and 754 enlisted men, although *Knyaz Suvorov* carried 928 crewmen during the Battle of Tsushima.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The *Borodino*-class ships were powered by two 4-cylinder triple-expansion steam engines, each driving one propeller shaft, using steam generated by 20 Belleville boilers.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The engines were designed to reach a top speed of 18 knots (33 km/h; 21 mph).
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The lead ship, *Borodino*, was fitted with a copy of the La Seyne machinery installed in *Tsesarvich* and built by the Franco-Russian Works.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The remaining four *Borodino*s were supplied with machinery designed and built by the Baltic Works.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] *Borodino*'s engines were rated at 16,300 indicated horsepower (12,200 kW) and its boilers had a working pressure of 19 atm (1,925 kPa; 20 kgf/cm2); the machinery of her sisters was rated at 15,800 ihp (11,800 kW) and their boilers had a working pressure of 21 atm (2,128 kPa; 22 kgf/cm2).
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Other differences were that *Borodino* was equipped with economisers for her boilers as well as three-bladed screws, while her sisters lacked economisers and had four-bladed propellers.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Because the ships were being prepared to go to the Far East shortly after completion, they conducted only abbreviated sea trials.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Only *Oryol* reached her designed speed during these trails, despite her engines producing only 14,176 ihp (10,571 kW).
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The engines of her sisters produced more power, but they were slower during their trials.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] At deep load they carried 1,350 long tons (1,372 t) of coal that provided them a range of 2,590 nautical miles (4,800 km; 2,980 mi) at a speed of 10 knots (19 km/h; 12 mph).
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The ships were fitted with six steam-driven generators with a total capacity of 738 kilowatts (990 hp).
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The main armament of the *Borodino* class consisted of two pairs of 40-caliber 12-inch guns mounted in French-style, electrically powered, twin-gun turrets fore and aft.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The turrets had a maximum elevation of +15° and 60 rounds per gun were carried.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The guns fired one shell every 90–132 seconds.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The secondary armament of the ships consisted of a dozen 45-caliber Canet Model 1891 6-inch (152 mm) (QF) guns mounted in six electrically powered twin-gun turrets on the upper deck.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The turrets had a maximum elevation of +15° arc of fire and the center turrets could cover 180°.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Each six-inch gun was provided with 180 rounds.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Their rate of fire was about 2–4 rounds per minute.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] They fired shells that weighed 91 lb (41.4 kg) with a muzzle velocity of 2,600 ft/s (792.5 m/s).
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] They had a maximum range of approximately 12,600 yards (11,500 m).
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] A number of smaller guns were carried for defense against torpedo boats.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] These included twenty 50-calibre Canet QF 75-millimetre (3 in) guns mounted in hull embrasures.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The ships carried 300 shells for each gun.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] They fired a 11-pound (4.9 kg) shell at a muzzle velocity of 2,700 ft/s (820 m/s) to a maximum range of 7,005 yards (6,405 m) at an elevation of +13°.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The *Borodino*-class ships also mounted sixteen or eighteen 47-millimetre (1.9 in) Hotchkiss guns in the superstructure.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] They fired a 2.2-pound (1.00 kg) shell at a muzzle velocity of 1,400 ft/s (430 m/s) at a rate of around 15 rounds per minute.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The ships carried four 381-millimetre (15 in) torpedo tubes, two of which were mounted above water in the bow and stern while the two broadside underwater tubes were located near the forward 12-inch magazine.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Four torpedoes were carried for the above-water tubes and six for the submerged tubes.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] They also carried 50 mines to be laid to protect their anchorage in remote areas.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The *Borodino* class were originally fitted with Liuzhol stadiametric rangefinders that used the angle between two vertical points on an enemy ship, usually the waterline and the crow's nest, to estimate the range.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The gunnery officer consulted his references to get the range and calculated the proper elevation and deflection required to hit the target.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] He then transmitted his commands via a Geisler electro-mechanical fire-control transmission system to each gun or turret.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] While fitting out, these rangefinders were replaced on the first four ships by two Barr and Stroud coincidence rangefinders that used two images that had to be superimposed to derive the range.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Perepelkin telescopic sights were also installed for their guns, but their crews were not trained in how to use them.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The waterline armor belt of the *Borodino*s consisted of Krupp armor and was 5.7–7.64 inches (145–194 mm) thick.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The armor of their gun turrets had a maximum thickness of 10 in (254 mm) and their deck ranged from 1 to 2 inches (25 to 51 mm) in thickness.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The 1.5-inch (38 mm) armored lower deck curved downwards and formed an anti-torpedo bulkhead.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] On 15 October 1904, *Knyaz Suvorov*, flagship of Vice Admiral Zinovy Rozhestvensky, commander of the 2nd Pacific Squadron, and the other three *Borodino*-class battleships set sail for Port Arthur from Libau along with the other vessels of the squadron.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Rozhestvensky had received numerous reports of Japanese agents and torpedo boats disguised as fishing vessels before sailing and he ordered maximum alertness after coaling at Skagen, Denmark on 7 October.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Early on the evening of the following day, when the squadron was near the Dogger Bank, the auxiliary repair ship *Kamchatka* reported that she was under attack by torpedo boats in the rain.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] About four hours later, the squadron encountered British fishing trawlers working the Dogger Bank in the fog and opened fire on them at very short range.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] One trawler was sunk and at least three others were damaged; several fishermen were killed and others wounded.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The battleships also fired upon and damaged the cruisers *Aurora* and *Dmitrii Donskoi* in the confusion.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The incident enraged the British population and caused a diplomatic incident with the British that nearly led to war until Russia apologized and agreed to pay reparations on 29 October.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Rozhestvensky led his ships down the Atlantic coast of Africa, rounding the Cape of Good Hope, and reached the island of Nosy Be off the north-west coast of Madagascar on 9 January 1905 where they remained for two months while Rozhestvensky finalized his coaling arrangements.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] During this time, he learned of the capture of Port Arthur and changed his destination to Vladivostok, the only other port controlled by the Russians in the Far East.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The squadron sailed for Camranh Bay, French Indochina, on 16 March and reached it almost a month later to await the obsolete ships of the 3rd Pacific Squadron, commanded by Rear Admiral Nikolai Nebogatov.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The latter ships reached Camranh Bay on 9 May and the combined force sailed for Vladivostok on 14 May.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] While exact figures are not available, it is probable that the ships were approximately 1,700 long tons (1,727 t) overweight as they were overloaded with coal and other supplies; all of which was stored high in the ships and reduced their stability.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The extra weight also submerged their waterline armor belt and left only about 4 feet 6 inches (1.4 m) of the upper armor belt above the waterline.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Before the battle Rozhestvensky grouped the four *Borodino*s into one division and retained personal command of the division.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] *Oryol*, the last ship in the division, fired the first shots of the Battle of Tsushima when the ship's captain, Nikolay Yung, ordered her to open fire at 11:42 at a Japanese cruiser that was shadowing the Russian formation at a range of 9,000 meters (9,800 yd).
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Rozhestvensky had not given any pre-battle instructions to the fleet covering this situation, but he ordered Yung to cease fire after 30 rounds had been fired without effect.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] *Knyaz Suvorov* was the lead ship in the Russian battle line and she opened fire at the Japanese battleship *Mikasa*, flagship of Admiral Tōgō Heihachirō at 14:05.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] *Mikasa* and the other Japanese ships began to return fire about five minutes later.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Their high-explosive shells quickly set all four of the *Borodino*s on fire; at 14:35, Rozhestvensky and the *Knyaz Suvorov*'s captain were wounded by splinters that entered the ship's conning tower.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Around 14:52, another hit jammed *Knyaz Suvorov*'s steering gear after a four point turn to starboard had been ordered and caused the ship to make nearly a full circle before she could be steered by her engines.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] By this time *Knyaz Suvorov*'s aft 12-inch gun turret had been destroyed by an explosion that blew its roof off onto the quarterdeck, her forward funnel had fallen down and her mainmast had been shot away.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] When the shooting between the battle lines resumed around 18:00, the Japanese concentrated their fire upon *Imperator Aleksandr III* and *Borodino*.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] *Imperator Alexandr III* sheered out of line to port around 18:30 and capsized, but did not sink until 19:07; there were no survivors.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] *Borodino* lasted a little while longer under concentrated Japanese fire.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Two 12-inch hits by the battleship *Shikishima* at 19:18 started a massive fire and both the ship's 12-inch gun turrets were knocked out.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Ten minutes later, after Tōgō ordered his ships to cease fire and disengage, the battleship *Fuji* fired her already-loaded 12-inch guns before turning away.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] One of these hit *Borodino* beneath her starboard forward six-inch turret and ignited the ready-use ammunition in the turret.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The fire spread and caused a catastrophic detonation in several magazines that blew open her hull.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] *Borodino* quickly capsized and sank with only one crewman from her crew of 855 being rescued.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The Japanese substantially rebuilt *Oryol* and recommissioned her in June 1907 with the name of *Iwami*.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] To reduce her top weight, they cut down her superstructure and repositioned her guns.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] In addition, her boilers were replaced by an unknown number of Japanese-built Miyabara boilers and she was rearmed with Japanese-made guns.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] These changes reduced her displacement to approximately 13,500 long tons (13,717 t) and her crew now totaled 750 officers and crewmen.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] During World War I, the ship participated in the Siege of Tsingtao in August–November 1914 and served as the flagship of the Japanese Intervention Squadron in Vladivostok in 1918 when Japan intervened in the Russian Civil War.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] She was used as a training ship in 1921 and disarmed in 1922 in accordance with the terms of the Washington Naval Treaty.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Sources differ as to her ultimate fate; she was either sunk as a target by aircraft near Miura in July 1924 or scrapped at Kobe in 1924–1925.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] Serving in the Baltic Sea during World War I, *Slava* was the largest ship of the Russian Gulf of Riga Squadron that fought the German High Seas Fleet in the Battle of the Gulf of Riga in August 1915.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] She was lightly damaged by three hits during the battle.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] She repeatedly bombarded German positions and troops for the rest of 1915 and during 1916.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] During the Battle of Moon Sound in 1917, *Slava* was badly damaged by the German dreadnought SMS *König* and the flooding significantly increased her draft.
[src:antony-preston/borodino-class-battleship] The shallow channel made it impossible to escape and she was scuttled in the Moon Sound Strait between the island of Muhu (Moon) and the mainland.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] The **K-class submarines** were a class of steam-propelled submarines of the Royal Navy designed in 1913.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Intended as large, fast vessels with the endurance and speed to operate with the battle fleet, they gained notoriety and the nickname of "Kalamity class" for being involved in many accidents.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Of the 18 built, none were lost through enemy action, but six sank, with significant loss of life, in accidents.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Only one ever engaged an enemy vessel, *K-7* hitting a U-boat amidships, though the torpedo failed to explode with what has been described as typical "K" luck; *K-7* escaped retaliation by steaming away at speed.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] The class found favour with Commodore Roger Keyes, then Inspector Captain of Submarines, and with Admirals John Jellicoe, Commander-in-Chief of the Grand Fleet, and David Beatty, Commander-in-Chief Battlecruiser Squadrons.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] When the class was designed, the use of submarines was still in its infancy.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Submarines, which later acted only by stealth, are no longer expected to be within a surface warship formation.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] In 1913, a design outline was prepared for a new class of submarine which could operate with the surface fleet, sweeping ahead of it in a fleet action.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] It was intended that the submarines would get behind the German High Seas Fleet and ambush it as it retreated from the superior British Grand Fleet.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] The boats were to be 339 feet (103 m) long and displace 1,700 tons on the surface.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] It was decided not to proceed until results from trials of two prototypes, *Nautilus* and *Swordfish*, had taken place.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Following the trials with *Nautilus*, the slightly smaller J class (1200 tons) was designed with a conventional diesel propulsion system.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] It was judged that the only way to give submarines sufficient surface speed to keep up with the fleet was to power them by steam turbines.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] The K-class design was resurrected and 21 boats ordered in August at a cost of £340,000 each.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] These boats were ordered without performing tests beforehand with a prototype, because the country was at war and submarines were urgently needed.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Only 17 were constructed, the orders for the last four being cancelled and replaced by orders for the equally large M class.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Six improved versions, *K22* to *K28* were ordered in October 1917, but only *K26* was completed by the end of the First World War.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] The double hull design had a reserve buoyancy of 32.5 per cent.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Although powered on the surface by oil-fired steam turbines, they were also equipped with an 800 hp (600 kW) diesel generator to charge the batteries and provide limited propulsive power in the event of problems with the boilers.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] This pushed the displacement up to 1,980 tons on the surface, 2,566 tons submerged.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] They were equipped with four 18-inch (460 mm) torpedo tubes at the bow, two on either beam and another pair in a swivel mounting on the superstructure for night use.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] The swivel pair were later removed because they were prone to damage in rough seas.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] The K-class submarines were fitted with a proper deckhouse, built over and around the conning tower, which gave the crew much better protection than the canvas screens fitted in previous Royal Navy submarines.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] The great size of the boats (compared to their predecessors) led to control and depth-keeping problems, particularly as efficient telemotor controls had not yet been developed.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] This was made worse by the estimated maximum diving depth of 200 feet (61 m) being much less than their overall length.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Even a 10-degree angle on the 339-foot-long hull would cause a 59-foot (18 m) difference in depth of the bow and stern, and 30 degrees would produce 170 feet (52 m), which meant that while the stern would almost be on the surface, the bow would almost be at its maximum safe depth.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] The submarines were made more dangerous because the eight internal bulkheads were designed and tested during development to stand a pressure equivalent to only 70 feet (21 m), risking their collapse if the hull was compromised at a depth below this figure.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] A dive from steam-powered surface operation normally required 30 minutes.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Minimum time needed to secure the main engines, shift to battery motors and dive under emergency conditions was nearly 5 minutes, which, though better than the 15 minutes of the *Swordfish* prototype, was considered barely adequate.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] The main intake ventilators were likewise closed along with sea water connections for condensers and boiler feed.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] It was considered that with their 24 knots (44 km/h; 28 mph) of speed the submarines could turn and outrun almost any threat if they were attacked on the surface, dispensing with a need for a rapid dive.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] This perhaps just excused the fact that the fast 'crash dives' of conventional submarines were unattainable.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] The high temperatures in the boiler room were problematical; this was to some extent alleviated by installing bigger fans.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Steaming at speed tended to push the bow into the water, making the already poor sea-keeping worse.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] To fix this a bulbous *swan bow* was added, which also incorporated a 'quick blowing' ballast tank to improve handling.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Nevertheless, there were still problems with seaworthiness, such as that in a heavy storm, sea water could enter the boat through the short twin funnels and put the boiler fires out.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Submariners were 'Volunteers Only,' and the class reputation as being designated 'K' for Kalamity (or Killer) did little to endear them to their crews, or provide a steady stream of volunteers.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] With a dive time of around 5 minutes (with the record being 3 minutes 25 seconds which was claimed by *K8*) it allowed the captain the luxury of being able to walk around the superstructure to ensure that the funnels were securely folded.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] The last, improved, boat, *K26* was completed slowly, being commissioned in 1923.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] She had six 21-inch (530 mm) bow torpedo tubes but retained the 18-inch beam tubes.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Her higher casing almost cured the problems of seawater entering the boiler room, and improved ballast tank arrangements cut the diving time to 3 minutes 12 seconds to get to 80 feet (24 m).
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] She also had an increased maximum diving depth of 250 feet (76 m).
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Most were scrapped between 1921 and 1926 but *K26* survived until 1931, then being broken up because her displacement exceeded the limits for submarine displacement in the London Naval Treaty of 1930.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] *K18*, *K19* and *K20* became the new M-class submarines.
[src:antony-preston/british-k-class-submarine] Although the concept of a submarine fast enough to operate with a battle fleet eventually fell out of favour, it was still an important consideration in the design of the River class in the late 1920s.
